<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Late President Yang Shangkun Cares for Country, People  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Late Chinese President Yang
Shangkun, who died of illness early this week in Beijing at the
age of 92, continued to show great concern about the country and
people during his last days of life.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who retired from official posts in 1993, was hospitalized
on June 7 as his state of illness worsened.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with President Jiang Zemin on August 19, Yang
smiled in relief after Jiang told him that the Party Central
Committee and the State Council had taken effective measures to
counter the grave floods along the Yangtze, Nenjiang and Songhua
rivers and assured him that the Chinese people could overcome
the temporary difficulties.
</P>
<P>
While talking with Premier Zhu Rongji about the devastating
floods, Yang said: "I am happy that you have the right ways for
flood control."
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
and Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing, all members of the
Standing Committee of Political Bureau of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) Central Committee, all visited Yang during his
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
Liu Ying, widow of late veteran revolutionary Zhang Wentian,
Wang Guangmei, widow of late Chinese President Liu Shaoqi, Zhu
Lin, widow of late Leader Deng Xiaoping, Zhang Jiqing, widow of
Peng Zhen, late chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, many
relatives of Yang's comrades-in-arms, and people from southern
Guangdong Province, where Yang worked between 1978-1980, among
many others, also visited or sent flowers to Yang while he was in
hospital.
</P>
<P>
As a great revolutionary, Yang concerned himself with majors
issues at home and abroad and with China's reform, opening-up and
socialist modernization cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Late President Yang Shangkun Cares for Country, People  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While watching a program of the China Central Television on
document falsification by some grain supply enterprises, he said
worriedly "we suffered from falsification in the past and why
should some places continue to falsify?"
</P>
<P>
When he learned from TV reports that some flood-control workers
fell on the river dyke after consecutive days and nights of hard
work, Yang said "we should learn from them."
</P>
<P>
However, on hearing that some local officials had committed
dereliction of duty on the flood-control frontlines, Yang said
angrily that such officials should be investigated and punished.
</P>
<P>
In early August, Yang asked his children to donate 20,000 yuan,
which was his and his wife's bank savings, to the flooded areas to
be used for purchasing medicines.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis was always on Yang's mind. He told
people around him that with the firm backing of the motherland,
Hong Kong would tide over the temporary difficulties caused by the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
On September 2, Yang called together members of his family and
told them that "man must die and you must not be too sad."
</P>
<P>
"As to my funeral matter, you'd ask the central government to
make it simple and even simpler as our country has suffered grave
disasters," Yang told his family.  
</P>
</TEXT>
