<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Set to Withdraw Troops from S.Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The British government
announced Thursday that it would withdraw its military detachment
of some 15 servicemen on the south Atlantic island of South
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
British Armed Forces Minister Doug Henderson told reporters
that Britain's garrison on the Falkland Islands would remain
responsible for the security of South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Henderson stressed that British military patrols in the area
would continue, saying:"If military support is required, we have
plans in place to make sure it will be provided promptly and
efficiently."
</P>
<P>
The British minister also noted that the British Antarctic
Survey (BAS), a government scientific body, would establish two
new sites on South Georgia for its work on the ecosystem of the
southern Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Britain has a 2,000-strong garrison on the
Falklands, some 800 miles (1,300 km) northwest of South Georgia,
which, along with the neighboring South Sandwich islands, is a
Falklands dependency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
