<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Records $13.9 Bln Deficit in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit
climbed up to 13.9 billion U.S. dollars in July, the Commerce
Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department statistics showed that the July deficit was 2.1
percent higher over June's revised imbalance of 13.6 billion
dollars. That made July the third-highest monthly deficit on
record, surpassed only by May and April of this year.
</P>
<P>
The worsening situation in July reflected a big jump in the
U.S. deficit with Pacific Rim countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with Pacific Rim countries, which includes
hard-hit South Korea, Thailand and Indonesia, rose by 5.1 percent
in July and for the first seven months this year totals 87.8
billion dollars, a 42 percent above the imbalance for the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
This country's deficit with Japan narrowed slightly to 5.2
billion dollars in July but so far this year is still running 16
percent above the 1997 pact.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky is in Tokyo this
week, pressing for further market-opening measures to narrow the
deficit in preparation for a meeting between President Bill
Clinton and new Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi in New York
next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The July overall trade deficit reflected a 1.3 percent drop in
U.S. exports to 75.4 billion dollars, the lowest level since
February 1997. U.S. imports were also down, but by a smaller 0.8
percent to 89.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The drop in exports reflected a 0.6 percent decline in sales of
farm products, which fell to 3.8 billion dollars in July and so
far this year are running 7.2 percent below the 1998 level.
</P>
<P>
Sales of American autos and auto parts dropped by 863 million
dollars in July while sales of telecommunications equipment were
down 166 million dollars and sales of computer products fell by
166 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. import decline was led by a 1.2 percent
drop in foreign oil, which fell to 4.07 billion dollars as the
average price per barrel of oil dipped to 10.71 dollars, the
lowest since August 1986.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the trade deficit in goods and services is
running at a record annual rate of 185 billion dollars, 68 percent
higher than last year's deficit of 110 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
