<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tri-Nation Probe Fails to Determine Validity of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Releasing its long-awaited report Thursday, the South
African-led commission, appointed by the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), said however it does have serious
concerns about apparent irregularities in the polls.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties claimed the May elections, which
saw the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) win 79 of 80
seats of parliament, were rigged.
</P>
<P>
"We are unable to state that the invalidity of the elections
has been conclusively established," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"We point out, however, that some of the apparent
irregularities and discrepancies are sufficiently serious
concerns.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot, however, postulate that the result does not
reflect the will of the Lesotho electorate."
</P>
<P>
The commission, which also included members from Zimbabwe and
Botswana, pointed out that the means for checking this had been
compromised and created much room for doubt.
</P>
<P>
The 10-member commission said that on its calculations, the
Basotho National Party (BNP), an opposition party, appeared to
have won two rather than only one in a total of 80
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
However, this related to a constituency the ballot papers of
which were not accessible to the commission.
</P>
<P>
The government of the tiny mountain kingdom was paralyzed
Wednesday as opposition parties' supporters forced civil servants
to leave their offices in an intensified protest against the
delay in releasing the report.
</P>
<P>
But later Wednesday, opposition parties said they would reject
the report whatever the findings might be. 
</P>
</TEXT>
