<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Wants Liberian Refugees to Leave by Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Ghana has warned all Liberian
refugees to leave the country by December 31 this year, or they
will lose their status, a report reaching here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Ghana Refugee Board said in Accra Wednesday that after the
deadline, all the refugees intending to stay will have to apply
for immigrant status.
</P>
<P>
Ebenezer Blavo, chairman of the board, was quoted as saying
that the new measure is introduced in view of the poor responses
of Liberian refugees to the voluntary repatriation exercise being
carried out by the Ghanaian government and the United Nations
High Commission for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation in Liberia has returned to normal and
that all refugees are expected to accept repatriation.
</P>
<P>
"Those who wish to stay in Ghana will be interviewed and those
found to have genuine fears will be made to stay as refugees.
Those with nothing to fear will have to apply for immigrants
status," the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Blavo also said that refugees who thought they could get visas
to travel to the U.S. or Europe if they remain as refugees should
discard that notion "because nothing of that sort exists".
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that about one million Liberians fled their
country during the 1989-1997 civil war. Thousands of them fled
into Ghana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
