<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls on Iran, Taliban to Solve Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Minister of
Information Nasir Judeh on Thursday called on Iran and Afghan
Taliban militia to settle their disputes through dialog instead of
military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by Jordan`s official news agency, the
Petra, Judeh said that "Jordan always asks for dialog among
conflicting parties to solve their differences."
</P>
<P>
Peaceful means and quiet dialog will serve the interests of
the region and enhance its stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan always calls for respecting human rights everywhere as
well as attaching importance to abidance of international
legitimacy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on Tuesday
ordered Iranian armed forces to be on alert and get ready for
taking revenge on Taliban for killing nine Iranian diplomats and
reporter.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Iran and the Taliban militia have mounted
since the killing of the nine Iranians in Mazari Sharif on August
8 when Taliban occupied the city in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
