<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Calls for Reform of Global Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain, the current president
of the Group of Seven (G7) industrial countries, has called for
urgent reform of the international financial system which has been
found wanting in the current global crisis.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Byers, Chief Secretary to the Treasury, told a London
conference Thursday that British Chancellor of the Exchequer
Gordan Brown would make a number of proposals to reform the
existing international institutions.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that they (financial institutions) have been found
wanting and need changing. Britain will be taking the lead in
this," Byers said, "We have benefited from the accelerating
integration of the international economy. Now we must manage it
through more difficult times."
</P>
<P>
"I believe the essential answer to the problems of the moment
is not less globalization, not new national structures to separate
and isolate economies, but stronger international structures to
make globalization work in harder times as well as easy ones," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that the urgent need is "closer
cooperation, continuing dialogue and an unwavering commitment to
open commerce." "We must not let temporary instability put global
progress at risk."
</P>
<P>
Byers noted that Chancellor Brown would be having extensive
discussions with the other G7 countries -- Canada, France,
Germany, Italy and the United States -- over the the next three
weeks on this issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Call for Lifting Sanctions on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Foreign
Ministerial Council Thursday expressed support to Libya's demand
for guarantees for a fair trial of the Lockerbie case and called
for suspending U.N. sanctions against Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Libya has rejected a new U.S.-British decision to accept the
trial in the Hague before Scottish judges without ensuring the
safety of the accused during transit and after the trial should
they be convicted.
</P>
<P>
The two were accused of blowing up an American plane in 1988
over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people. The
U.N. imposed air, arms and diplomatic embargo on the country in
1992 after it failed to hand over the two Libyans.
</P>
<P>
Top diplomats from the Arab League (AL)'s 22 member states made
their stance clear at the end of their two-day meeting in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions should be suspended immediately after (Libya)
reaching an agreement with the parties concerned on arrangements
and guarantees for putting the two Libyan suspects to trial before
the court," said a resolution issued by the council.
</P>
<P>
The council also recommended "the complete lifting of sanctions
against Libya immediately after the two suspects stand trial."
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League will act according to this basis," said the
resolution, without specifying what it will do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
However, in a draft resolution issued Wednesday, the council
toed a tougher line, saying that it is considering to bypass the
U.N. sanctions on Libya if its demand for a fair trial is not met.
</P>
<P>
The draft proposes stopping compliance with the sanctions
unless the "parties concerned" agree to negotiate with Libya on
these guarantees.
</P>
<P>
But in the resolution issued Thursday, the conferees expressed
the discontent of the Arab countries over the adverse impact the
international embargo has upon the Libyan people.
</P>
<P>
The council also condemned threats calling for tightening
sanctions imposed against Libya.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council welcomed the decision adopted by Britain
and the United States on accepting the proposals, presented by the
AL and Libya on putting the two Libyan suspects to trial before a
neutral court. The two countries had insisted on having the trial
in either of them.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain, who had been demanding extradition of the
Libyans to either of them, insisted that their offer is
non-negotiable.
</P>
<P>
This resolution, albeit a water-downed version of the draft, is
viewed by observers as an attempt by the 22-member Arab forum to
court back Libya.
</P>
<P>
Tripoli on Sunday decided to disband its Ministry of Arab Unity
in the coming few weeks, a move revealing its grudge against Arab
failure to have the U.N. sanctions against the Afro-Arab country
lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
