<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Promises Efforts to Defuse Iran-Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz on Thursday promised to make more efforts to defuse
the spiraling tensions between Iran and the Afghan Taliban
militia.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi, Aziz
voiced Pakistan's readiness to make efforts to return the bodies
of two other Iranian diplomats killed by the Taliban and release
other Iranians under the Taliban's captivity.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is serious to make efforts to release Iranians
arrested by the Taliban, and I hope we will see the result in
the coming days," the Pakistani minister was quoted by the
Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Aziz arrived here Thursday afternoon to deliver a message from
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami, in an effort to prevent a possible military
confrontation between Iran and the Taliban after Tehran built up
tens of thousands of troops along Afghanistan's western border.
</P>
<P>
Iran's supreme leader and commander-in-chief Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei on Tuesday ordered the Iranian armed forces to be on
the alert and maintain full readiness for "speedy, timely and
decisive implementation of whatever decisions the senior
political and security authorities deem necessary and right for
the country."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also expressed hope that Pakistan and the Taliban
would take immediate measures to return the bodies of two more
Iranian diplomats, release arrested Iranian nationals, and
identify, arrest and deliver those responsible for killing
Iranian diplomats for trial.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban on Monday delivered the bodies of six Iranian
diplomats and an IRNA reporter after admitting killing nine of
the 11 Iranians captured in Mazari Sharif, northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officials are under heavy pressure to take military
actions to punish the criminals, Kharrazi said, adding that
there is a limit for Iranian officials to bear the pressure and
surely the practical steps taken by Pakistan and the Taliban
would help reduce the pressure and improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iranian Foreign Ministry believed that before
resorting to force, a chance should be given to political and
international efforts to persuade the Taliban to revise their
past behaviors and to stop massacres in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the need to set up an international mechanism to
prevent further massacres in Bamyan, the center of the Afghan
Shiite Muslims conquered by the Taliban in recent days, and
other parts of Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
