<HEADLINE> U.N. to Hold International Meeting on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.
Secretary-General, Kofi Annan, will convene an international
meeting on Afghanistan at the ministerial level here on Monday
next week, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Invited to attend the so-called "six plus two meeting" are
foreign ministers from six of Afghanistan's neighbors, namely
China, Iran, Pakistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Uzebekstan, plus
Russia and the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came one day after the United Nations had
agreed to send a humanitarian assessment panel to Bamiyan, an
Afghan province which fell to the militant Taliban faction last
week, on condition that the Taliban guarantee the security of the
U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting, which is being held on the sidelines of
the United Nations General Assembly, will focus on crisis
embroiling Iran and the Taliban that has threatened to flare
into war.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began with the recent killings of at least eight
Iranian diplomats and a journalist by Taliban forces, which
control most of Afghanistan, during an attack on the Iranian
consultants in the northern town of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The proposed talks are also seen as an opportunity of the
highest-level diplomatic contact in nearly 20 years between Iran
and the United States, observers here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
