<HEADLINE> Cyprus Demilitarization Only Way to Cancel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The only way to cancel the
deployment of Cypriot government purchased Russian-made S-300
anti-aircraft missile system is demilitarization of the island,
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while commenting on statements by Turkish
Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan that "the only point
that would be meaningful for Turkey is the complete scrapping of
the missile order."
</P>
<P>
Stylianides told reporters that "the reply is simple. President
Glafcos Clerides has made a proposal for demilitarization of
Cyprus, and U.N. resolutions urge toward this direction."
</P>
<P>
He said that "if Turkey wishes to see the postponement of the
deployment of new armaments, this the only way."
</P>
<P>
"We do not accept anyone dictating to us our defense planning,
especially Turkey which is the only party responsible for tension
in the region and the only party creating problems in efforts for
a dialog aiming at the reduction of armaments on the island," the
spokesman stressed.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides also pointed out that the Cyprus problem is
exclusively an international political problem and not a problem
of missiles.
</P>
<P>
"The answer to those who wish for disengagement from military
plans is demilitarization and it is on the table," he said,
adding that "what we are waiting for is the Turkish negotiator."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called upon the international community to
realize that Turkey refuses to participate in such a dialog,
which he said is "the only reasonable and peaceful dialog."
</P>
<P>
Tensions have risen on the island ever since the Cypriot
government announced in January last year that it would deploy the
Russian missiles.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of the missiles, originally scheduled for August,
has been delayed until the end of this year due to international
pressure on the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkey continues to threaten that it will strike the
missiles if and when they reach Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot administration has insisted that the missile deal
can be canceled only if there is progress in the peace process
or a move toward demilitarization of the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
