<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Iran in Dilemma to Revenge on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The call and support for a military revenge on the
Taliban are growing throughout the country after the paramount
leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on Tuesday ordered the armed
forces to be on high alert.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei called on officials of the country, including the
armed forces, to maintain full readiness for "speedy, timely and
decisive implementation of whatever decisions the senior
political and security authorities deem necessary and right for
the country."
</P>
<P>
"Blood must atone for blood" has become a common sense here as
the whole nation is angered by and can not tolerate the Taliban
massacre of eight Iranian diplomats and a correspondent of the
official news agency IRNA on August 8 in Mazari Sharif, northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces, including the army, the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC), the security and Basij (volunteer) forces,
have announced their readiness to carry out Khamenei's order
anywhere and in any conditions.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC and the Iranian army have deployed over 200,000 troops
along the 850-kilometer border with Afghanistan as tension has
been escalating between Iran and the Afghan Taliban which has
seized most parts of country.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian troops has been flexing muscle these days by
launching military manoeuvers along the border and the army is
scheduled to launch another war game in the area, the biggest
after the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, later this month, apparently
getting ready for a showdown with the Afghan Taliban. The Taliban
authorities have denied any direct involvement in the killing and
flatly refused to hand over those culprits to the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
A war of some kind or a military strike seems unavoidable and
imminent, but how? Observers and diplomatic circles here believe
a limited military action against the Afghan new rulers might be
the option if no way out for the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
However, Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi stressed on Wednesday
that "before taking military actions against the Taliban, a
chance should be given to political and peaceful approaches in
order to protect the country's national interests."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi's remark was a clear signal that the government of
President Mohammad Khatami did not hope to be militarily
involved in Afghanistan in view of the bitter experience of
former Soviet Union in Afghanistan and nightmares of the
Iran-Iraq war in 1980-88.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
