<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Sky Is Shrinking, Scientists Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found that the
sky has shrunk by eight kilometers in the last 40 years, British
newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers of the British Antarctic Survey in Cambridge
believed that the contraction is probably a result of the
greenhouse effect, the Daily Telegraph said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The new study, which probed 40 years of data gathered at the
Antarctic peninsula and the Falkland Islands, reveals for the
first time that the shrinkage is global, Dr Jarvis, one of the
researchers, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The scientists made the discovery when they analyzed records of
40-year-old experiment to bounce radio waves off the ionosphere,
the electrically charged part of the upper atmosphere composed
mainly of ionised gases.
</P>
<P>
The radio waves have been taking less times to return than they
did in 1958, which scientists said could only be explained by a
fall in the ionosphere's height.
</P>
<P>
The effect is believed to be the carbon dioxide build-up. When
carbon dioxide accumulates in the upper atmosphere, the gas causes
the atmosphere to cool, resulting in a drop in barometric pressure
and the shrinkage of the ionosphere.
</P>
<P>
Although the drop in altitude is not in itself harmful to
people, "it is, however, another warning signal about what changes
to the atmosphere can be caused by human impact." Dr Jarvis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
