<HEADLINE> Russian Grain Output Nearly Halved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 17 (Xinhua) -- As a devalued ruble forces
prices up daily, and sometimes hourly, the Russians will have to
cope with more bad news, this time a nearly 50 percent drop in
grain harvest and possibly a record low in four decades.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Statistics Committee, Russian farmers
had only harvested 41.8 million tonnes of grain by Monday, a
little more than half as recorded in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
It confirmed fears that the country is heading for its worst
harvest in four decades, the Interfax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Production of potatoes and other vegetables as of September 14
also went down, by 15 percent and 3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The drop was attributed to drought and other bad weather
conditions this Summer. 
</P>
