<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Owes Pension Board 23M Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
owed the public service pension board 46 billion Kwacha (about 23
million U.S. Dollars) in unremitted dues, hampering the borad's
move to invest members' contributions, board officials said.
</P>
<P>
Board Chairman Donald Chanda and Secretary Offman Gondwe were
qu by Times of Zambia Thursday as saying that the board wants
to invest its members' contributions in business but could not
start because of the huge debt the government owed them.
</P>
<P>
Chanda, who is also Zambian President Frederick Chiluba's
economic adviser, said Wednesday, "we want to recreate the whole
institutions in terms of operations. We want to invest the
contributions in meaningful investment to provide growth. We want
the board to stand on its own and pay beneficiaries immediately."
</P>
<P>
Gondwe said since the new board and management took office in
June this year, a total of 4.4 billion Kwacha (about 2.2 million
Dollars) has been paid to 1,429 pensioners.
</P>
<P>
He said of the 43,000 pensioners on the waiting list, 1,580
have already been earmarked for payment as soon as the country's
ministry of finance released the money.
</P>
<P>
Gondwe said the board is also holding discussions with the
National Credit and Savings Bank and Zambia Postal Services on
the opening of new pay points in provinces and districts to make
it easier to get their money. 
</P>
