<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secession Labeled as "Misdirected" by Zambian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
described an opposition party's call for the secession of Western
Province as "misdirected and unfortunate."
</P>
<P>
Government-owned Times of Zambia Thursday quoted chief
government spokesman David Mpamba as saying in an interview in
Lusaka Wednesday that secession would not solve Zambia's economic
and political problems.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba, also Information and Broadcasting Minister, stressed
that Zambia had been a unitary state for nearly 34 years and to
call for a breakdown into tribal enclaves would not help.
</P>
<P>
Akashambatwa Mbikusita-Lewanika, president of Agenda for
Zambia (AZ) and member of Barotse Royal Establishment, said
Monday his party would consider facilitating a referendum on
former Barotseland's status because his tribesmen there had been
marginalized under tte central government.
</P>
<P>
"If tribalism is the problem, let us address ourselves to that
problem rather than destroy our country," said Mpamba.
</P>
<P>
He called on young Zambians who knew no tribal boundaries to
discard tribal sentiments and unite to build one strong Zambia
without taking people like Mbikusita-Lweanika seriously.
</P>
<P>
Western Province Minister Michael Mabenga also said Wednesday
that it was unfair for the AZ leader to guess all the people in
his province wanted to break away from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Barotseland, which got its present name in 1969, enjoyed half
independence under British colonial rule and strove to become an
independent state before it became part of Zambia soon after the
country won its independence in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Besides the opposition party, a group calling itself the
Barotse Patriotic Front on Self-Determination last month
circulated brochures in the capital city, demanding the
independence of Western Province from Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
