<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mediators Urged to Speed up Peace Plan in G. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has asked the two
groups set up to resolve the political crisis in Guinea Bissau to
implement their peace plan in the country as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) Thursday quoted Nigerian
Foreign Minister Ignatius Olisemeka as saying in capital Abuja
that the parameters should include a time-table for negotiations
and the establishment of an observer group.
</P>
<P>
The minister said at the opening of the meeting of foreign
ministers of the groups Wednesday that the peace plan should
indicate the composition and placement of the interposition of
troops between those loyal to President Joao Vieira and rebel
leader Gen. Ansumane Mane.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two groups, the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) Committee of Seven and the contact group
of the Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries (CPSC), to
examine the various recommendations of their chiefs of staff and
military experts who had met earlier.
</P>
<P>
Olisemeka assured the meeting that Nigeria would continue to
work together with its partners in the search for " lasting peace
for Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
He said Nigerian Head of State Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar,
ECOWAS Chairman, had expressed the hope that the on-going
deliberations would result in concrete and firm guidelines which
would provide the path for the early restoration of peace and
security to Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Ghana, Gambia, Guinea, Cote d'Ivoire, Liberia, Nigeria and
Senegal are members of the ECOWAS Committee of Seven while
Angola, Brazil, Cape Ver'e, Portugal and Sao Tome and Principle
constitute the contact group of the CPSC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
