<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Urges Arab Countries to Support Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Thursday urges
Arab countries to extend support to Sudan in its struggle against
the worst floods in centuries and renewed U.S. threats of attacks.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the League Secretariat called upon Arab
countries to render aid to Sudan to help it sidestep the impact of
the floods and torrential rains that hit most parts of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The floods, which swept 10 provinces in central, northern
and eastern parts of Sudan, has inundated 119,000 houses and left
204,000 families homeless.
</P>
<P>
The league expressed hope that the Arab countries would help
alleviate the suffering of the Sudanese people who are affected by
the floods.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the 22-member Arab forum Thursday
called upon its member states to rally around Sudan in face of the
U.S. threats to launch new military attacks against it.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministerial Council, in its resolution issued at
the end of its two-day meeting, said the U.S. bombing attacks
against Sudan last month "trampled on Sudan's sovereignty and
territorial integrity, violated the international laws and the
U.N. Charter."
</P>
<P>
"We support Sudan's struggle against threats to its
sovereignty, territory and national unity and its appeals to
various organizations to rule out military means as a way out to
solving problems," it added.
</P>
<P>
The resolution condemned various kinds of terrorism, whether
from "a state, a group or individuals" and called for positive
political dialog to resolve dispute.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. bombardment on a chemical plant near Khartoum on
August 20 has left a number of civilians dead and flattened a
facility providing the country with 50 percent of its needs of
medicines.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched the attacks in what it claimed retaliation
for the twin bombings against its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
on August 7. It has accused Sudan of sponsoring international
terrorism and claimed the factory was manufacturing chemical
weapons agents that could be used by Islamic militants to launch
new attacks against U.S. targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
