<HEADLINE> Reservation of African Cultural Heritages Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of
Information and Culture Woldemichael Chemu Thursday urged African
countries to preserve properly their cultural and historical
heritages.
</P>
<P>
Opening a meeting here attended by curators from 13 African
countries, the Ethiopian minister said the cultural and
historical heritages of Africa have not been cared for.
</P>
<P>
Chemu said the historical relics of Africa have not been kept
properly at museums and that they have not been registered.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed the need for experts to look for ways of
setting up relic institutions and share among themselves
experiences in the field to bring Africa to a better standard in
documentation organization.
</P>
<P>
The two-week meeting on preservation in museums of Africa was
organized by the international center for the study of the
preservation and reservation of cultural property.
</P>
<P>
The center was established in 1956 by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultu2al Organization (UNESCO) and
has 94 countries as its members around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
