<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Pushing for Moratorium of Military Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain is pushing for a
possible agreement on a moratorium of Greek and Turkish military
flights over Cyprus, a senior British official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides, Peter Rickets, senior official at the British Foreign
Office dealing with the Cyprus problem, told reporters that "what
we're doing is working up the practical arrangements that would
make a moratorium possible. That's the focus of our efforts at the
moment."
</P>
<P>
Rickets confirmed that British Defense Secretary George
Robertson had discussed this issue with his Greek and Turkish
counterparts during his visit to Athens and Ankara this week,
saying his country "will continue to press for the moratorium."
</P>
<P>
However, he refrained from saying whether the moratorium
would be internationally guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Rickets also met with Cypriot Foreign
Minister Ioannis Kasoulides, and he is scheduled to meet with
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in the Turkish-controlled
northern part of Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
"We are working particularly with the American government and
in Cyprus, Athens and Ankara to reach an agreement on the
practical content of an overflight moratorium, that's where
Britain can play a particular part," Rickets said.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for a moratorium of Greek and Turkish military
flights over Cyprus was put forward by the U.S. last year. The
Cypriot government, backed by Athens, however, insisted that a
no-fly zone over Cyprus should be guaranteed by international
powers.
</P>
<P>
Rickets noted that his country "remains very active in the
search for a peaceful settlement in Cyprus under the U.N. process."
</P>
<P>
"My visit here is part of that continuing efforts," he said,
adding that he had a detailed discussion with Clerides "about ways
with which we can push forward the U.N. process in Cyprus, and
Britain will continue to work actively to that end."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern one third of the island in the
wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks hit snag last summer when
Denktash walked out of a direct talks between the two community
leaders in Switzerland to protest against a European Union
decision to start accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has recently proposed a confederation of the two
communities as a basis for resumption of peace talks, but the
proposal has been rejected by the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Greece and Turkey were the guarantors of Cyprus'
independence under the 1960 Treaty of Establishment of the
Republic of Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
