<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Ready for New Partnership With Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A top World Bank official
said Thursday that the bank is ready to form a new partnership
with Nigeria, as the most populous African country is beginning a
new political and(economic transition period.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here at the end of his five-day
visit to Nigeria, the bank's Vice-President for Africa,
Jean-Lousis Sarbid said he was "encouraged by recent development"
in Nigeria under the new leadership of General Abdulsalam
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria has recently entered a period of transition in both
the political and economic realms," he said. "This has rekindled
hope, and the World Bank is ready to help Nigeria pursue that
hope."
</P>
<P>
Sarbib's visit is the first by a high-level World Bank
official to Nigeria in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Nigeria and the World Bank has been frosty
since 1993 under the leadership of late General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
From September 13 to 17, Sarbid met with Nigerian leader
Abubakar and top government officials, including the ministers of
Finance, Planning, Education, Health and Agriculture, and the
governor of the central Bank.
</P>
<P>
He also met with representatives of the private sector and
non-government organizations and visited primary schools and
health facilities.
</P>
<P>
Sarbid noted that Nigeria holds vast potential to become an
economic giant in Africa by virtue of its size, human talents,
rich resources endowment and economic capacity.
</P>
<P>
However, he regretted that "Nigeria has yet to live up to this
potential. Poor economic management, poor governance, corruption
and political instability have gotten in the way of development,
allowing poverty to spread in the midst of great affluence for a
privileged few."
</P>
<P>
Sarbid commended the recent political development in Nigeria
under General Abubakar, adding that "matching this with economic
momentum would help put the country on the road to economic
revival."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official identified economic management,
poverty, education, agriculture, health as well as the serious
world economic situation as major challenges facing the Nigerian
economy.
</P>
<P>
Stating that the bank is ready to enter into new partnership
with Nigeria, Sarbib said officials from Nigeria and the bank
will meet soon in Washington during the World Bank's annual
meeting to pick up specific priorities in which the bank might
provide assistance.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice-president, the World Bank has provided a
total of seven billion U.S. Dollars in fund commitment to
projects in Nigeria since 1958.
</P>
<P>
The bank currently has 13 projects in Nigeria in the fields of
agriculture, water, urban development, education, population,
health and roads, with a total fund commitment of about one
billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank, however, has provided no new loans to Nigeria since
1993, when relations between the two sides got sour.
</P>
<P>
Sarbid confirmed that some projects have been canceled by the
bank because of delay in implementation.
</P>
<P>
The bank would not let the fund lie there idle for as many as
seven years when there is a great demand in other African
countries, he explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
