<HEADLINE> More Ethiopians Escape from Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 38 Ethiopians
arrived in Djibouti Sunday and Monday from Eritrea, a government
spokeswoman said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Selome Taddesse said in a statement that 17 of them arrived in
Djibouti by boat after escaping from Assab in south Eritrea,
while 21 of them traveled by car or on foot.
</P>
<P>
Taddesse quoted the escapees as saying that it took up to 10
days for them to reach Djibouti, and some of them had failed to
make it through the desert and have probably died there.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokeswoman, these escapees are traders,
skilled and semi-skilled laborers and drivers and they had lived
in Eritrea between three and 21 years.
</P>
<P>
The official says, "without exception they all had previously
been arrested, beaten and all had their property confiscated."
</P>
<P>
Over 15,000 Ethiopians have been expelled from Eritrea since a
border conflict between the two countries erupted in May, this
year. However, Eritrea says up to 17,000 of its nationals have
been expelled from Ethiopia since the border dispute. But the
Ethiopian government says those "deported for security reasons"
were only around 4,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
