<HEADLINE> Russian Ruble Crashes Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Russian ruble continued
sliding Thursday, and the Central Bank said it would print money
to pay off state debts and bail out banks.
</P>
<P>
The ruble, which lost some 30 percent of its value on the
streets of Moscow Wednesday, dropped to 15.80 to the dollar on the
SELT electronic trading system of the Moscow Interbank Currency
Exchange (MICEX), down from Wednesday's official rate 12.4509 to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
A dollar was worth 6.5 rubles a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Kozlov, first deputy chairman of the Central Bank, told
a press conference that some money must be printed if GKO T-bills,
or government debts, are to be bought back.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank plans to carry out a transaction
Friday aimed at settlement of interbank payments in Moscow, the
greater Moscow Region, St. Petersburg, Samara Region, and
Sverdlovsk region, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kozlov said some money from the Mandatory Reserve Fund may be
used for the settlement, adding that the central bank, to
replenish the fund, will suggest the banks to sell their packages
of GKO and OFZ securities maturing before December 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The amount of rubles to be printed will be exactly equal to the
amount the banks need to pay their payments, Kozlov said.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we will inject money into the system. The amount needed
cannot be determined and the percentage will be announced tomorrow
when the records are available," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
