<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Kuwaiti Minister of Commerce and Industry Abdul Aziz
al-Dekheel Thursday opened the Kuwait products exhibition here in
a bid to increase his country's market in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 Kuwaiti companies took part in the five-day fair in
which they display garments, plastics, electronics, tools and
petrochemical products.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is eager to improve the balance of trade with
Lebanon which is currently not in its favor.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's exports to Kuwait in 1997 stood at 60 million
U.S. dollars against 3 million dollars of imports.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's central bank governor Riad Salameh has
suggested that all banks in the country use credit and debit
cards as well as the electronic network to complete all
transactions.
</P>
<P>
He said at a conference here Wednesday that the central
bank would soon submit a recommendation to the government
asking it to authorize the proposal, the Daily Star reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He called on all Arab countries to establish a joint
electronic payment network to facilitate easy transactions among
Arab banks and financial firms.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Central Bank of Jordan (CBJ) recently predicted
that the growth rate of Jordan's gross domestic products (GDP) in
1998 will be 2.5 percent, the kingdom's leading Arabic daily Al
Ra'I reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The CBJ is obviously more pessimistic about Jordan's economy
than the government, who forecast the growth rate at 6 percent
and then lowered it to 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Royal Jordanian (RJ) signed an agreement with the
Austrian Airlines on Wednesday to increase weekly flights between
Amman and Vienna from three to six, Jordan's official news
agency, the Petra, reported.
</P>
<P>
It said that the agreement will take effect on October 25.
</P>
