<HEADLINE> Sudan Floods Get Worse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The flooding Nile has
devastated Sudan's Northern State for more than 1,000 kilometers,
the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies (IFRC) said in a statement issued here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"These floods are being reported as the worst since 1988 but
in many places the water is already much higher than then. These
could be the worst in living memory," Omer Osman Mahmoud, chief
of the Sudanese Red Crescent, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The flood "has engulfed villages on either bank, inundated
farmland, and left most of the rural population homeless," a
Sudanese Red Crescent field team flying over the deluge reported.
</P>
<P>
"All populated areas (were) under water and only mountainside
homes surviving," the IFRC statement quoted a team report as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"In southeastern Marawi Province, no village has escaped on
the the southern bank, and few are still intact on the northern
one," it said.
</P>
<P>
In Dongola Province, much of the land lies lower than the
river and protective dikes have been washed away or are in danger
from the rising water, the IFRC statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the international agency appealed to the
international community for three million Swiss Francs (about
2.13 million U.S. Dollars) to support its relief projects in
flood-hit and war-torn Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan People's Liberation Army has re-started fighting
with the Moslem-led Khartoum government since 1983 for more
autonomy and religion freedom in the animist and
Christian-dominated south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
