<HEADLINE> Turkey, India Vow to Enhance Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Turkey and
India Suleyman Demirel and K.R. Narayanan vowed here on Thursday
to develop bilateral ties in an all-round way, according to local
TV reports.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after a meeting with his
Indian counterpart, Demirel said that there is no major problems
between Turkey and India and the bilateral ties have proceeded
smoothly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Calling India a close ally of Turkey, Demirel said that there
is great potential for the two countries to enhance bilateral
ties, particularly in economic areas.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Narayanan, who arrived Wednesday for a five-day
visit to Turkey, said that his country has always attached great
importance to its ties with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"In Turkey I really feel at home," said Narayanan, who served
as the Indian ambassador to Ankara during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, however, also made complaint over the nuclear race
between India and its rival Pakistan, saying that the contest
would cause the southern Asia more unstable.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is against the proliferation of nuclear weapons," the
Turkish president said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Indian-Pakistan confrontation in Kashmir,
Demirel called on the two countries to solve the problem in a
peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
"We wish that the problem would be solved in a way acceptable
to both sides and in accordance with the principles of
international legitimacy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and Indian officials signed four agreements on mutual
protection and promotion of investments, cooperation against
drug-smuggling, improvement of exports, exchanges of science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Demirel said that the
current bilateral trade volume of 360 million U.S. dollars does
not reflect the real potentialities of the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
