<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Spacecraft SOHO Re-points to The Sun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- After weeks of recovery
efforts, the SOHO solar spacecraft is once again pointing at the
Sun, the European Space Agency (ESA) announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
SOHO obeyed commands that turned its face fully towards the Sun
on 16 September, a landmark day which was a culmination of complex
procedures that finally brought back the spacecraft under control.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time since 25 June, when SOHO spun out of
control and communication was lost, it points the right way." the
ESA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It's a big step forward in our recovery plan for SOHO," says
ESA's Francis Vandenbussche, head of the SOHO recovery team.
</P>
<P>
"We were never quite sure that we would manage to make the
spacecraft point back towards the Sun, which is essential for its
proper operation."
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that the next step will be a comprehensive
check of all the spacecraft's systems and scientific instruments,
which in some cases have been through an ordeal of heat or cold,
with temperatures approaching plus or minus 100 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Dr Bernhard Fleck, ESA's project scientist for SOHO, said he
is "cautiously optimistic that SOHO can win back much of its
scientific capacity for observing the Sun."
</P>
<P>
SOHO, the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory, operates at a
special vantage point 1.5 million kilometers out in space, on the
sunward side of the Earth. It is a joint project of ESA and U.S.
space agency NASA.
</P>
<P>
After its launch on 2 December 1995, SOHO worked a revolution
in solar science by its special ability observe simultaneously the
interior and atmosphere of the Sun, and particles in the solar
wind and the heliosphere.
</P>
<P>
Apart from amazing discoveries about flows of gas inside the
Sun, giant "tornadoes" of hot, electrically charged gas, and
clashing magnetic field-lines, SOHO also proved its worth as the
chief watchdog for the Sun, giving early warning of eruptions that
could affect the Earth.
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, SOHO's scientists celebrated two years of
successful operations, and the decision of ESA and NASA to extend
the mission to 2003.
</P>
<P>
The extension would enable SOHO to observe intense solar
activity, expected when the count of sunspots rises to a maximum
around the year 2000. It would remain the flagship of a
multinational fleet of solar spacecrafts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
