<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jrodan, PNA Accuse Israeli Monopoly of Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian and Palestinian
government officials here Thursday accused Israel of trying to
keep monopoly over the Palestinian markets by blocking others from
conducting trade exchanges with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Obstructing implementation of the economic and trade agreements
between Palestine and Jordan is one of the ways Israel is
attempting to monopoly over the Palestinian markets, Chairman of
the Jordanian Trade Chamber Federation Haider Murad said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli obstruction keeps the volume of
Jordanian-Palestinian trade exchanges far less than expected, said
Murad at the 1998 Jordanian-Palestinian economic and trade talks
which were opened earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, the
Jordanian-Palestinian trade exchanges only reached 10 million
Jordanian dinars (about 14 million U.S. dollars), according to
Murad.
</P>
<P>
Back in 1997, only 23 million dinars (32 million dollars)
worth of Palestinian-made products were exported to Jordan and
12 million dinars (about 17 million dollars) worth of
Jordanian-made goods to the Palestinian self-rule areas, Murad
added.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Palestinian delegation Khaled Salameh echoed
Murad's view, adding that by maintaining such a monopoly, Israel
intends to strangle the Palestinian economy and make the
Palestinians wholly dependent on Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians' annual purchases from Israel are worth 2.7
billion dollars to 4 billion dollars and account for almost
95 percent of their total imports, which is an extremely
abnormal phenomenon, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are coerced to import from Israel, while
the list of goods that they are allowed to buy from other
countries like Egypt and Jordan is very limited in kinds
and quantities, Khaled added.
</P>
<P>
Even as the list is limited, Israeli soldiers usually block
most of the commodities that the Palestinians import from other
countries at the the border crossings of the Palestinian
self-rule areas, according to Khaled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jordanian and Palestinian participants of the
talks unanimously called for collective efforts to confront the
Israeli measures designed to dominate the Palestinian markets.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that this can be done through unifying both
sides' economic laws and regulations and establishing new means
for trade exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Khaled proposed that it will be helpful in this regard if
both sides set up a Jordanian-Palestinian land transportation
company and other joint ventures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
