<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Russia Against Hyperinflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- There may be
hyperinflation in Russia if it fails to control spending and to
reform its banking and financial systems, a senior U.S. official
warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The warning was made by Deputy U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers in his remarks to the House International Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
"They must resist pressures to spend and lend which will doom
the economy to another bout of high, perhaps hyperinflation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Just as important, they need to take on the failings of the
financial system and finally put in place the core institutions
and policies of a private market economy," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
He said the steps Russia has taken so far to devalue and
restructure its debt are "drastic measures" that need explaining.
</P>
<P>
"Russia's authorities urgently need to clarify those steps and
begin a cooperative dialogue with official and commercial
creditors," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is difficult to shape an international effort to
help Russia through its current financial crisis because it is
unclear which direction Russian authorities are taking.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has pledged its support for Russia on the condition
that the new Russian government will continue a reform path, but
any cash aid will be made through international financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
