<HEADLINE> Albright to Meet Iranian FM on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will meet with Iran's foreign minister Kamal
Kharazi next week in New York, focusing on tensions between
Afghanistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the highest-level U.S. contact with Iran since the
1979 takeover of the American Embassy in Tehran, is part of an
eight-nation effort designed to head off a conflict between Iran
and Afghanistan's ruling Taliban regime.
</P>
<P>
"We obviously are concerned about what is going on between the
Taliban and Iran," Albright said Thursday in response to a
question after a luncheon speech to the Carnegie Endowment for
Peace.
</P>
<P>
Albright also reaffirmed the Clinton administration's interest
in improving relations with Tehran if it changes some of its
policies and halts what the United States says is support of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
She said she was very eager to see what Kharazi has to say in a
speech next Friday to the Asia Society in New York.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to be listening to see if there are any actions,"
Albright said, referring to new approaches by the Iranian
government that might fit the U.S. prescription for moderation.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan is setting up the conference
on Afghanistan. Albright plans to attend, and she said Kharazi had
decided to be there as well.
</P>
<P>
Iran, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Pakistan, China,
the U.S. and Russia will attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Iran and Afghanistan have escalated after the
nine Iranian diplomats were killed by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Kharazi and Albright will be at the United Nations next week to
attend the annual session of the U.N. General Assembly, during
which foreign ministers will hold bilateral meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
