<HEADLINE> Pakistani FM Delivers Sharif's Message to Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz on Thursday delivered a written message from Pakistan's
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to Iran's First Vice President Hassan
Habibi.
</P>
<P>
The message was scheduled to be delivered to Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami. The change was seen as a signal of Tehran's
anger over Islamabad's support for the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Aziz arrived here Thursday afternoon to deliver the message in
order to avoid possible tensions between Pakistan and Iran, after
Iran's spiritual leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei accused Islamabad
of helping the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Aziz assured
Habibi in the meeting that the Pakistani government would make
efforts to speed up the delivery of the bodies of two remaining
Iranian diplomats killed by the Taliban and the release of other
Iranian nationals captured by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran occupies a special position in Pakistan's
foreign policy and Islamabad is ready to expand and promote
relations with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Condemning the killings of eight Iranian diplomats and an IRNA
reporter by the Taliban, Aziz called for trial and punishment on
those responsible for the killing.
</P>
<P>
Habibi said that the Taliban's crimes against Iranian
diplomats and other Iranian nationals, as well as massacre of
Afghan Muslim people were actions against humanity and Islam.
</P>
<P>
He expressed dissatisfaction with Islamabad's support for the
Taliban and called on the Pakistani government to use its
influence on the Taliban to stop the killings of Afghan people,
to release the captured Iranian citizens and return the bodies of
remaining Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Habibi also stressed that the Taliban should make apology to
Iran and punish those responsible for the killing of the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban on Monday delivered the bodies of six Iranian
diplomats and a reporter after admitting killing nine of
the 11 Iranians captured in Mazari Sharif, northern Afghanistan.
</P>
