<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Lesotho
Congress for Democracy will not step down or call for new
elections as there was no elections fraud as alleged by the
opposition, Deputy Prime Minister Kalebone Maope said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted Maope as saYjng South
African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi had
suggested that a meeting of all the parties in Lesotho should
take place on Sunday to discuss the way forward.
</P>
<P>
"We have all been asked (by Mufamadi) not to comment on this
until we have some discussion, so I'm surprised the opposition is
calling for us to step down."
</P>
<P>
Referring to a call that the Lesotho government should step
down so that fresh elections could be held, Maope said: "There is
no need for that."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday afternoon, about 5,000 people gathered outside the
gates of King Letsie III's palace in capital Maseru, while being
briefed by leaders of Lesotho opposition parties on the contents
of the long-waited investigation report into alleged
irregularities in Lesotho's May general elections.
</P>
<P>
The crowd was told that a probe commission, which consists of
officials from South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe, had found
irregularities and discrepancies in the way Lesotho's independent
electoral commission had managed the May 23 general election.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition parties have claimed the results were
rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy,
which won 79 out of the 80 National Assembly seats.
</P>
<P>
However, the tri-national commission in its report said it
could not conclusively state that the elections were not valid.
</P>
