<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Fall on Dashed Hopes for Rates Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets
suffered steep losses on Thursday after sharp falls in Asia
overnight and with disappointment that U.S. Federal Reserve
chairman Alan Greenspan ruled out co-ordinated interest rate cuts
among leading central banks.
</P>
<P>
London had yet another dismal day with more than 30 billion
pounds or about 50 billion U.S. dollars wiped off the value of top
companies at one point. The FTSE 100 Index of top shares closed
down 158.8 at 5,132.9, a little above its session low of 5,101.5.
</P>
<P>
It followed overnight falls in the Far East and heavy falls in
the opening hours of trading on New York.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the gloom was the growing realization that a
co-ordinated cut in interest rates across major economic powers
was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the US Federal Reserve's chairman Alan Greenspan
said: "I think that I can safely say that at the moment there is
no endeavour to co-ordinate interest rate cuts."
</P>
<P>
The London fall came in the wake of big drops overnight in the
Far East. In Tokyo the Nikkei sank to levels last seen more than
12 years ago. Then the Dow Jones Industrial Average fell below
8,000 within moments of Wall Street opening at 2.30pm London time.
</P>
<P>
The market's rally over previous days had been based on
expectations of a co-ordinated cut in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
News that high street sales in August were better than expected
also appeared to cut the chances that interest rates in Britain
would be taken down soon by the Bank of England's Monetary Policy
Committee.
</P>
<P>
"This is the indication of the souffle market," said Justin
Urquhart Stewart, business planning director of Barclays
Stockbrokers. "As soon as you think it's cooked you take it out
the oven and it falls again."
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, Germany's benchmark Xetra Dax slipped nearly 5
percent, as a weaker opening on Wall Street did little to prop up
the feeble index amid ongoing market nervousness. The Xetra Dax
fell by 243.15 points to close at 4629.03. The Dax 30 index ended
the trading day down 188.5 points at 4669.5.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, share prices closed sharply lower following an
unprecedented sell-off in Alcatel, which lost about 40 percent of
its value, dragging down other engineering, defense and telecoms
stocks and the banking sector, notably key Alcatel shareholder
Societe Generale.
</P>
<P>
The Cac 40 index closed down 204.06 points, or 5.4 percent at
3,525.26.
</P>
<P>
The market fell steadily through the session after Alcatel
posted a weaker-than-expected first half income from ordinary
operations and warned that the second half figure would also be
below earlier forecasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
