<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Russia Against Returning to Soviet Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration on
Thursday warned Russia against returning to Soviet-style economic
systems and confrontation with the United States and the West.
</P>
<P>
There may be hyperinflation in Russia if it fails to control
spending and to reform its banking and financial systems, said
Deputy U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers at a hearing of
the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
Also testifying at the hearing, Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott said Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's
first appointments of economic officials in his new cabinet were
cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
The new Russian government would be under pressure from the
State Duma or the parliament to shift emphasis from cooperation
with the U.S. to confrontation and defiance, Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
"If that were to happen, if Russia were to move in foreign
policy in the direction they were moving in economic policy, it
would portend a double disaster for Russia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Central Bank earlier announced that it will print
money to pay wage and pension arrears.
</P>
<P>
"They must resist pressures to spend and lend which will doom
the economy to another bout of high, perhaps hyperinflation,"
Summers said.
</P>
<P>
"Just as important, they need to take on the failings of the
financial system and finally put in place the core institutions
and policies of a private market economy," Summers added.
</P>
<P>
He said the steps Russia has taken so far to devalue and
restructure its debt were "drastic measures" that need explaining.
</P>
<P>
"Russia's authorities urgently need to clarify those steps and
begin a co-operative dialogue with official and commercial
creditors," Summers said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was difficult to shape an international effort to
help Russia through its current financial crisis because it was
unclear which direction Russian authorities were taking.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has pledged its support for Russia on the condition
that the new Russian government will continue a reform path, but
any cash aid will be made through international financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
