<HEADLINE> China's Anhui Province Lifts State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The government of east China's
Anhui Province today declared an end to the 55-day state of
emergency along the Yangtze River that runs through the province.
</P>
<P>
The floodwater has receded and the water level of the Yangtze's
Anhui section has dropped to the danger mark and the focus of the
current work in this east China province has been shifted to the
work of rehabilitating local economy.
</P>
<P>
Anhui suffered devasting floods this summer, with the Yangtze's
water level topping the danger mark for 85 consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
However, thanks to water control works and flood prevention
facilities Anhui had built over the past decades, it has been
retrieved from a loss of some 45.7 billion yuan (5.5 billion US
dollars), local sources said.  
</P>
