<HEADLINE> Large Investment for Pollution Control in Southwest China Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans to invest a total
of 8.568 billion yuan (about 1.032 billion U.S. dollars) to control
the growing pollution in Dianchi Lake, a well-known fresh water
lake in southwest China, an environmental official said here today.
</P>
<P>
China aims to increase the sewage treatment rate around the
lake to 85 percent and return a good ecological environment to the
lake by 2010, Wang Jirong, deputy director of the State General
Administration of Environmental Protection, told a news conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
Dianchi, covering an area of 307 square kilometers on the
outskirts of Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan
Province, is the sixth largest fresh water lake in China.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid industrial development of Kunming city, the lake
was seriously polluted in recent years. More than 2,000 mines and
factories surrounding the lake discharge over 200 million tons of
waste water into the lake annually.
</P>
<P>
Wang said a plan made by the government of Yunnan Province in
order to control the contamination to the lake and improve its
surrounding environment has recently been approved by the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 projects will be initiated, said Wang, adding
that the World Bank will offer loans of 1.43 billion yuan (about
172 million U.S. dollars), and China has yet to raise more than
6.1 billion yuan (728 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
