<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Air Force Base Chosen as Lockerbie Trial Venue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands and Britain
Friday chose a Dutch air force base as the venue for the trial of
the two Libyan suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing of Pan Am
flight 103.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Foreign Minister Jozias van Aartsen and British
Ambassador to the Netherlands Rosemary Spencer signed the venue
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The trial venue is located at Camp Zeist within the Soesterberg
air force base close to the Hague, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the 15-member United Nations Security Council
endorsed a Britain-United States resolution to suspend sanctions
against Libya provided it handed over to the Netherlands the two
men suspected of the mid-air bombing that killed 270 people for
trial by Scottish judges under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
On December 21, 1988, Pan Am flight 103, flying from Frankfurt
to New York via London, exploded over Lockerbie killing 259 people
on board and another 11 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Investigations led to the accusation that two Libyan airline
company staff members stationed in Malta planted the explosive
device on Pan Am flight 103.
</P>
<P>
A warrant was later issued by Britain and the United States for
the arrest of Abdel Baset Ali Mohamed al-Megrahi and Al-Amin
Khalifa Fhimah who were charged with conspiracy, murder and
violation of the Aviation Security Act of 1982.
</P>
<P>
Libya, which demanded that the two suspects be tried only in a
third country, has not yet fully committed itself to extraditing
the two suspects for trial in the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
