<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier League Referees to Go Full-time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League
referees are set to be full-time, sponsored and aided by video
replays next season, the League's referees officer Philip Don
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Don indicated that full-time officials were set to be
introduced by 2000 along with video replays, which would be used
solely to rule on controversial goals.
</P>
<P>
And although the sponsorship of officials is currently
outlawed by FIFA, Don is confident that the new full-time
officials could be paid via sponsors' logos on their shirts.
</P>
<P>
"The Premier League wants to be pro-active on the issue of
professional referees," Don said.
</P>
<P>
"It's what a lot of people in the game want and we want the
referees to be assisted by technology.
</P>
<P>
"By the start of next season, we will have a number of
professional referees in the Premier League."
</P>
<P>
Don indicated that although referees' salaries were not
finalised, they would be in the region of 40,000-50,000 pounds
per year, and he added: "We have put an attractive package tog
ether to get the right referees and give them something to
justify giving up their day jobs."
</P>
<P>
Video replays would help referees with their decision-making,
Don said -- but he insisted they would only be used to determine
if a shot went in the goal or not.
</P>
<P>
"The ball crossing the goalline is fact, while the likes of
fouls and infringements are down to the referee's opinion," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Premier League spokesman Mike Lee said there had been
encouraging feedback from referees on the future of top-flight o
fficialdom.
</P>
<P>
And he added that League bosses would be contacting football's
other governing bodies for a full-scale discussion of the changes.
</P>
<P>
"The main points are the appointment of full-time referees and
video replays of controversial goals," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the proposals could be up and running for next season
but at this point they are just ideas under discussion and
nothing has been agreed yet.
</P>
<P>
"The thinking behind it all is to make sure there is
continuous improvement in refereeing standards and that we are
addressing the needs of the modern game.
</P>
<P>
"We're also taking into account much of the public debate that
goes on among fans about referees, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
