<HEADLINE> Cyprus Seeks European Help to Resolve Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- In a letter published here
Friday, Cyprus's Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou urged his
European counterparts to pressure Turkey to work toward a just and
viable solution of the Cyprus dispute.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, which has been sent to his European
counterparts, Omirou denounced Turkey for strengthening its
forces in northern Cyprus by upgrading their armaments.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has taken over the northern third of this Eastern
Mediterranean island in 1974 after a failed coup staged by Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has so far maintained a 35,000-strong armed forces in
northern Cyprus with the alleged aim of protecting the Turkish
Cypriots, who declared in 1983 the breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" that is only recognized by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Omirou called on his European counterparts to exercise their
influence over Turkey to reduce the military tension on the island
and to cooperate in settling the Cyprus issue based on
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization,
whose members include most Western countries in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been trying for decades to reunite the
divided island in a bizonal, bicommunal federation through peace
talks, but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
