<HEADLINE> Pakistani-Indian PMs to Discuss Resumption of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif's meeting with his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari
Vajpayee in New York next week will focus on ways and means to
resume the stalled dialogue between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz here Friday
after a news briefing on his one-day visit to Tehran on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, the foreign minister said that the
main purpose of the Nawaz-Vajpayee meeting would be to start the
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Vajpayee are expected to meet at a luncheon on the
sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly session, which
would be the second meeting between the two leaders since India
and Pakistan conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he thinks the foreign secretary-level talks between
Pakistan and India will resume after the prime ministers' meeting,
Aziz said "it depends on the meeting."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistani and Indian officials had discussed various
proposals in Durban, South Africa, which will be presented to the
two leaders.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister called for a meaningful dialogue with
India, saying that it should not only be a sitting.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretary-level talks between the two countries
collapsed in New Delhi last year due to the difference over the
Kashmir issue. Pakistan insists that Kashmir and the issue of
peace and security should be discussed separately while India
calls for composite discussion. 
</P>
