<HEADLINE> Allies to Stay Until Congo (K) Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has reiterated that President Laurent Kabila's military
allies would stay in the former Zaire until the situation there
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
In a statement broadcast by Zimbabwe State Television (ZTV)
Friday, Mugabe also said that more African states were ready to
back Kabila against Tutsi-led rebels.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the ZTV Thursday night after meeting Namibian
President Sam Nujoma who stopped over in Harare, capital of
Zimbabwe, on his way home from a state visit to Mozambique,
Mugabe said Kaibla's allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia --
had support from around the African continent.
</P>
<P>
"Many more African countries...not just from the SADC
(Southern African Development Community) are prepared to assist
the Democratic Republic of the Congo with troops whenever
President Kabila may need that help," Mugabe said without giving
further details.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe sent about 3,000 troops backed by warplanes and tanks
to the Congo (K) to defend Kabila against a rebellion which
started on August 2, which the Congolese leader blames on Rwanda
and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe justifies his military intervention in Congo (K),
saying that he went there as a matter of principle that a
government must not be overthrown through violence.
</P>
<P>
But his critics both at home and abroad said regional peace
efforts had been blunted by Mugabe's preferen for overall
military victory over the six-week rebellion.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Zimbabwean Defense Minister Moven Mahachi told
parliament the allied troops would remain in the Congo (K) until
they were convinced that permanent peace is restored in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said he shared Zimbabwe's view
and told the ZTV "we want peace in the region so that we can
concentrate on building our economies."
</P>
<P>
He also said the allied forces would help Kabila train his
army to enable it to deal with future invasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
