<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Syria Conduct Joint Naval Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and its closest ally
Syria have conducted joint naval maneuvers with live ammunition in
the Mediterranean, Lebanon's Voice of the People radio reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted a military source as saying that the maneuvers
were conducted Thursday with the participation of a Lebanese
military unit and Syrian forces.
</P>
<P>
Gen Ali Aslan, chief of staff of the Syrian armed forces,
attended the final stage of the maneuvers and urged the fighters
to keep a high level of combat readiness to confront any
aggression wherever it comes from.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon have strongly condemned the planned
Israeli-Turkish naval exercises in the Mediterranean, which were
announced following a visit by Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz to Israel earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
They said that the increasing military cooperation between
Israel and Turkey constitutes a threat to Arab national security.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has stationed 40,000 troops in Lebanon, vowed to
closely coordinate its stance with its tiny neighbor over regional
issues, especially the stance toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel have been occupying south Lebanon and Syria's Golan
Heights. Meanwhile, Turkey has been pointing an accusing finger at
Damascus for the alleged Syrian support for the Kurdish rebels
fighting to oust the government.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have been developing strategic ties since
early 1996 when they signed two military cooperation deals.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has allowed Israeli pilots to use its air space for
training, and Israel has been upgrading Turkish fighter planes
with its advanced technologies. 
</P>
