<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communist Party Members Urged to Donate Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li
Lanqing today urged members of both the Communist Party of China
(CPC) and the Communist Youth League of China to take the lead in
blood donation.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is also a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, made the call in a
letter to a national tele-conference to mark the promulgation of
China's first Blood Donation Law, due to become valid on October 1.
</P>
<P>
General public is also encouraged to donate blood to fulfil
their responsibilities and obligations as set in the law, Li said.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of the law signals a major change in the
use of blood for medical purposes and indicates that China's blood
administration work has entered a new period," the vice-premier
noted.
</P>
<P>
The enforcement of the law is of far-reaching significance to
safeguarding social stability and sustainable economic growth, he
said. He voiced his hope that leading officials at all levels, as
long as their health conditions and ages permit, will take the
lead in blood donation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenkang, minister of health, announced at the meeting
that one million medical personnel will join the team of blood
donors. He also asked government employees, servicemen and college
students to take the lead in the endeavor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he acknowledged that safety problems in blood
transfusion are becoming serious because of illegal blood deals.
</P>
<P>
"Diseases transmitted through blood transfusion, such as
hepatitis B and C, and AIDS, are endangering blood users' health
at any time," he told the meeting
</P>
<P>
The work of spreading blood donation has been cited as
"sluggish" since it was launched in 1984. A wrong but deep-rooted
opinion that donating blood may be detrimantal to one's health is
blamed as the major reason.
</P>
<P>
The milestone law, adopted by the National People's Congress,
China's highest legislative body, late last year, stipulates that
donated blood is only for clincal use.
</P>
<P>
The law specifies that government employees, servicemen and
college students should set as exemplary models in blood
donation. They are estimated to provide approxmiately 250 tons of
blood used for urgent use annually.
</P>
<P>
Family members and friends of the people who are going to
undergo operations are encouraged to donate blood, according to
the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
