<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Meets Visiting Irish Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa reaffirmed Hong Kong's commitment to free market here Friday
when meeting with visiting Prime Minister of Ireland Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
"We have a flexible market which allows very efficient price
adjustment for major production factors. We are aware that it is
necessary to allow market forces to bring our prices to a level at
which the market can afford. We are ready to take the pain arising
from the adjustment process," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
There has been immediate and huge adjustment in the property
market, Tung said, adding the adjustment process has been
extremely efficient.
</P>
<P>
"The labor market has also been undergoing adjustment, but this
will take some time," he told Ahern. Speaking from his former life
as a businessman, Tung pointed out that "employers must be caring
to their employees in the adjustment process in order to bring the
best out of their employees."
</P>
<P>
Ahern congratulated Tung on the successful implementation of
the "One Country, Two Systems" principle as the Special
Administrative Region is stepping into its second year after
returning to China. The prime minister believed that with
efficient market system the Hong Kong economy would rebound
quickly.
</P>
<P>
Tung told Ahern that with huge reserves and in the absence of
foreign debts, Hong Kong would continue to invest heavily in
education and infrastructure, and capitalize on its links with the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Irish investors are welcome to participate in the city's
infrastructure projects, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We are the most international city in Asia and are determined
to remain that way. We welcome investors to participate in our
developments from all over the world," Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
Ahern arrived in Hong Kong Thursday following a visit to the
Chinese mainland and will be leaving tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
