<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The House Judiciary Committee wrangled over whether to make
public a videotape of President Bill Clinton's grand jury testimony
in the Monica Lewinsky case and how to edit reams of pages
delivered by the independent counsel. The panel was expected to
approve the tape's release without any redactions.
</P>
<P>
-- Russia's new government indicated that it planned to satisfy
old debts and bail out old friends by printing billions of new
rubles. In Washington, Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence H.
Summers said Russia was heading toward a return to four-digit
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The disclosure of a 30-year-ago extramarital affair by House
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J. Hyde (R-Ill.) provoked an
extraordinary display of acrimony Thursday as Republicans tried to
blame the tory on the White House and presidential aides
complained that they were being unfairly smeared.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Congress moved swiftly Thursday to provide stopgap
funding for the government while it tries to resolve major
disputes over spending for next year, including a bitter fight
over new U.S. contributions to the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- IMF (International Monetary Fund) funding was opposed in a
229-188 House vote that could force the White House to compromise
on its request for 17.9 billion U.S. dollars to fund accounts
drained by the Asia crisis. The vote blocked IMF backers from
bringing up the request in debate on a foreign-aid bill.
Republicans are demanding an overhaul of agency procedures.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton attacked an 80 billion U.S.
dollars GOP tax-cut package as a threat to Social Security and a
possible signal of U.S. fiscal laxness, but the House Ways and
Means panel passed it 23-15. The House, worried about looming
budget fights, took steps to keep the government open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
