<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Weathers Asian Financial Crisis (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade have
chalked up a comparatively high growth, and basically weathered
the Asian Financial turmoil, a senior trade official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian financial crisis have impacted China's foreign trade
and resulted in weaker growth in the export business this year,
said Sun Zhenyu, vice-minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, at an international seminar on China's economy and
investment climate.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he added, "the growth in export is still
relatively strong as compared to the plunging export of
neighboring nations."
</P>
<P>
But Sun acknowledged that the prospect for China's foreign
trade is not so optimistic and the trade surplus is expected to
decline further next year.
</P>
<P>
"With the Asian financial crisis worsening and its impact still
spreading, it will be virtually impossible for the export sector
to maintain a high growth," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister went on to say that he expects to see a great
increase in the import business next year and, as a result of the
government's growing investment and recovering domestic
demand. And he added that the government will work to achieve a
trade balance in the import and export next year, and expect a
smaller trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China scored 179.5 billion US dollars in
foreign trade volume during the first seven months this year, up
4.2 percent over the same period last year. Export to the United
States, Europe, Africa and Latin America maintained growth of more
than 18 percent, compared to the sharp decline to eastern and
southeastern nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Weathers Asian Financial Crisis (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign investors in Europe and America have become even more
enthusiastic to invest in China, as is indicated in the more than
39 percent growth in actual investment by 15 EU nations, US and
Canada during the first half year.
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign investment during the January-July period
totalled 23.9 billion US dollars during the period, up 7.3 percent
from last year.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister also noted in his speech that the Chinese
government will continue implementing its opening-up, while taking
a cautious and positive approach in doing that.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China will continue to gradually open up the service
sector to investors from overseas, Sun noted, and the opening of
the financial and telecommunications sectors is also expected to
widen.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade is expected to reach 400 billion US
dollars in next three years by the end of this century, said the
vice-minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports of Ho Chi Minh City Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Exports from Ho Chi Minh City
this year are expected to drop to 3.7 billion U.S. dollars, 11.5
percent less than last year, Ho Chi Minh City trade service
reported.
</P>
<P>
Export receipts for Ho Chi Minh City, the largest economic hub
in Vietnam, in the first nine months of 1998 were estimated at 2.8
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the trade service, the fall resulted from the cut
in price of several items, especially key export items.
</P>
<P>
The price-cut caused a 400-million-dollar loss in crude
exports, 50 million dollars in rubber and pharmaceutical
materials, and 120 dollars in garments, said the trade service.
</P>
<P>
Another cause for the export reduction was the weather pattern
and natural disasters which have badly affected the output of
agro- and aqua-products.
</P>
<P>
The drop could also be attributed to the fact that Vietnam's big
export markets, such as Japan, Indonesia, South Korea, the Association
of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) and northeast Asian
countries, had cut their imports from Vietnam, because of their
austerity policies or difficulties in pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The stock market of the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
sharply plummeted Thursday to close at 4895.53 points, down 100
points from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the Abu Dhabi National Bank index that
fell below the level of 5,000 points in the past month.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts believed that the sharp fall of the UAE stock
market was largely because that a group of investors, particularly
smaller ones, had sold their stocks in order to buy new shares to
be offered to augment the capital of several companies.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian stock market declined last week in
terms of both the trading volume and value, the Arabic-language
daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the market closed at 163.6 points from 165.93
points last Thursday, a decline of 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Only the share prices of five companies closed higher on
Thursday, and those of 18 other companies remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The market's general index has so far lost 32.33 points or 16.5
percent since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Affected by fears about the deepening world economic
crisis, Turkey's Istanbul Stock Exchange fell to the 14-month low
of 1,948 points Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The National-100 index shed 8.4 percent on Thursday due to the
investors' frustration over the lack of a clear program to help
pull the world out of the current economic depression.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts said the share prices of many Turkish
companies have dropped by nearly two-thirds since July.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors have lost at least 5 billion U.S. dollars
in Turkey alone as a result of the falling stocks.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The current account deficit in Israel fell by
almost 50 percent in the first half of 1998 compared with the
same period last year, from 2.3 billion U.S. dollars to 1.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics published Friday said that Israel's overall
foreign debt grew by 2 billion dollars to stand on 17.5 billion
dollars in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in Israel in this period totaled 1.2
billion dollars, a decline of 300 million dollars compared with
the previous year. Israel's overseas investments also fell to 100
million dollars from 400 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Recent turmoil in Israel's currency markets helped
push the Consumer Price Index 0.5 percent higher in August,
bringing the annual rate of inflation to an average 4 to 5
percent, official statistics published Friday said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli currency shekel has shed more than 5 percent of
its value against the dollar during last month's global market
mayhem, plunging to as low as 3.86 shekels for one dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
