<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, September 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said
Friday that Pakistan is ready to establish a commission with Iran
to determine the nature and level of external interference in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after his one-day visit to Iran
Thursday, Aziz said Pakistan is ready to work closely with Iran at
the United Nations, the Organization of Islamic Conference or any
other forum to resolve the present crisis between Iran and
Afghanistan. (Pakistan-Iran-Afghanistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- The ruling State Peace and Development Council (SPDC)
of Myanmar on Friday poured scorn on moves by an opposition
"People's Parliament" to take over the government of the country.
</P>
<P>
An government statement issued here said, "The government of
Myanmar noted with interest the announcement by the National
League for Democracy (NLD) on September 17 that it has formed a
10-person committee that will serve as a parliament to govern
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
"The current government will continue to shoulder the real
responsibilities of governing Myanmar, and will continue the
National Convention that is writing a constitution that will lead
to a stable, sustainable democracy in Myanmar," it concluded.
(Myanmar-Politics)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The World Meteorological Organization's (WMO's)
fifth regional association has elected Lim Joo Tick of Malaysia
as its new president for the 1998-2002 period, replacing
Dr. Karjoto of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Lim beat rival John R. Lumpsden of New Zealand in the 12th
conference of the Regional Association V (Southwest Pacific) of
the WMO in Denpasar, Bali of Indonesia, on Friday, according to
Antara News Agency. The WMO has 185 members divided into six
regional associations. (Indonesia-WMO-President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The Albanian parliament on Friday morning voted
overwhelmingly to strip the parliamentary immunity of Sali
Berisha, chairman of the Albanian Democratic Party, and opening
the way for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the move has paved the way for further
investigation of the former president's responsibility in this
week's riots in Tirana. (Albania-Berisha-Immunity) 
</P>
</TEXT>
