<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner to Get Award for Banning Tobacco Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's Social
Affairs Commissioner is to get a special award for his efforts to
ban tobacco advertising and promote public health, commission
sources said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn will be presented with the award at the biannual
European Respiratory Society Conference on Saturday in Geneva
which will be attended by about 10,000 delegates.
</P>
<P>
The respiratory society is grateful to the commissioner for his
success in securing an agreement on a Europe-wide ban on tobacco
advertising and sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
Flynn's success has been described as the most positive
development in public health protection in years.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission and the European Council of Ministers
agreed earlier in the year to ban tobacco advertising and
sponsorship of sports and art events in the future.
</P>
<P>
The ban is expected to become fully effective by 2006 at the
latest.
</P>
<P>
Smoking has been blamed for killing half a million citizens
each year in the European Union alone.
</P>
<P>
"If we fail to take measures to reduce that (fatality) figure,
we are failing in our primary responsibility to citizens:
protecting their health and well-being," said Flynn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
