<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Use and Sale of Leaded Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The State General
Administration of Environmental Protection today made known a
State Council circular that requires the country's gasoline
producers to stop producing leaded gasoline by the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
The State Council also demands that all the gas stations
replace leaded gasoline with unleaded on July 1, 2000, and that
automobile companies produce vehicles adapted for the use of
unleaded gasoline.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has decided to raise taxes on leaded gas
consumption and keep its price at least as high as unleaded
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jirong, deputy director of State General Administration of
Environmental Protection, told a press conference today that lead
emitted by automobiles from 1986 to 1995 exceeded 15,800 tons,
making it a major source of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the move to ban leaded gasoline will not only reduce
air pollution, but also spur China's auto industry to apply
advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
At present, 22 provinces and cities have worked out detailed
plans to abandon leaded gasoline, of which, 18 provinces and
cities including Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, have begun using
and selling unleaded gasoline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Mining Company Asked to Leave Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian Mining giant WMC
Ltd. should pull out of the Philippines because it was doing
social and ecological harm there, a delegation told the company
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, a mining watchdog of Philippine
representatives, met WMC Ltd. officials at the company's Melbourne
office to voice their protest, the Australian Associated Press
reported from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The delegation delivered a report by the Mineral Policy
Institute that criticizes the social and ecological impact of the
company's bid to develop Tampakan copper mine on the Philippines
island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The institute also alleges that WMC is overriding the wishes of
local people; destroying indigenous sites; leaving behind
radioactive waste; and removing native forests.
</P>
<P>
WMC Ltd. also had a poor track record for injuries and
inadequate safety at its operations in Australia and in other
countries including Papua New Guinea, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Philippine delegate Avelino Sichon accused the company of
failing to consult local people, of misusing land and destroying
the social fabric of the area's B'Laan tribe.
</P>
<P>
Pastor Avelino of the Alliance For Genuine Development in the
Philippines, representing farmers and others, said, in an area
beset by poverty, WMC was mining about 99,440 hectares of
agricultural and forested land belonging to the indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
About 240,000 B'Laan people live on the island, with 6,000 in
the area fenced off by WMC. They fear their remaining 10,000
hectares of virgin forest in the area will be destroyed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The company signed a financial and technical agreement with the
Philippine government in 1995 for the copper mining project.
</P>
<P>
"They are using the water for drilling and there is the
experience of the community that they get skin disease off their
drilling activity," Avelino said.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Drake, WMC's group manager of public affairs and
environment, attended the meeting and denied the accusations.
However, he said his company would examine the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
