<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Blood Donation Law to Become Effective in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister of Health
Zhang Wenkang has urged local governments to ensure implementation
of the country's first blood donation law, due to become effective
on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Zhang today announced that one million medical personnel will
join the team of blood donors. He also asked government employees,
servicemen and college students to take the lead in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The minister admitted that safety problem in blood transfusion
is becoming serious due to illegal blood deals.
</P>
<P>
"Diseases transmitted through blood transfusion, such as
hepatitis B and C, and AIDS, are endangering blood users' health
at any time," he told a national tele-conference on mobilization
of the law's enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Commercial blood suppliers who are detected HCV (hepatitis C
virus) positive several times or ten-odd times the blood donors,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the law has given us a legal weapon to punish
offenders and to protect people's health," Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
The work to spread blood donation has been described as
"sluggish" since it was launched in 1984. A wrong but
deeply-rooted opinion that donating blood may harm health is
blamed as the major reason.
</P>
<P>
The milestone law was passed by the National People's Congress,
China's highest legislative body, late last year, which stipulates
donated blood is clinically used only.
</P>
<P>
The law says government employees, servicemen and college
students should set a model in donating blood. They are estimated
to provide about 250 tons of blood used for urgent aims annually.
</P>
<P>
Family members and friends of people who are going to receive
operations are encouraged to donate blood, according to the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
