<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Subway, Elevated Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior official said here
today that China will speed up the construction of urban rail
traffic systems including suburban railways, subways and elevated
railways in the country's cities.
</P>
<P>
Ye Rutang, vice-minister of construction, said at the opening
ceremony of the '98 Seminar on City Rail, that China welcomes the
establishment of solely foreign-funded or Sino-foreign jointly
funded ventures for manufacturing subway rolling stock and
locomotives.
</P>
<P>
He said Shanghai, China's leading industrial city, has begun
building a 62-kilometer elevated railway project, and the line is
expected to open by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Ye said the capital city of Beijing is preparing to build a
suburban railway line in the northern part of the city.
</P>
<P>
He added that another 20 big and medium-sized cities including
Chongqing in southwest China and Qingdao in east China's Shandong
Province will soon start building subways.
</P>
<P>
So far, only four Chinese cities including Beijing and Shanghai
have subway systems.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of science and technology, said
during the opening ceremony of the three-day seminar that China
will employ a number of scientists and technicians to develop
domestic locomotive and rolling stock production while continuing
to introduce advanced technology from developed countries.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 government officials and businessmen from
China, Canada, Germany, Switzerland and other countries are
participating in the seminar jointly sponsored by the Ministry of
Science and Technology, and the ministries of construction and
railways.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference will also explore possibilities
for promoting Sino-foreign cooperation in the field of urban rail
traffic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
