<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Import and Export Bank of
China (IEBC) plans to provide 3.2 billion yuan in credit loans to
two major enterprises in south China's Guangdong Province, the
country's largest exporter.
</P>
<P>
This effort is aimed at strengthening export-oriented
electronics and machinery enterprise competitiveness in the world
market, and promoting China's overall foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The IEBC signed a related framework agreement worth 2 billion
yuan with TCL Electronics Corporation today in Huizhou in
Guangdong Province, and tomorrow will sign a similar 1.2 billion
yuan agreement with Guangzhou Shipyard International Co., Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The bank's vice-president, Gu Mingchao, who attended today's
signing ceremony in Huizhou, said his bank will continue to follow
the state policies regarding the industrial, foreign trade and
financial sectors, and provide strong capital support for the
export of electronics and machinery products.
</P>
<P>
The bank has financed approximately 2 billion yuan in credit
loans for the two enterprises since 1995 in a bid to stimulate
their exports.
</P>
<P>
TCL, a state-owned multinational corporation, produces color
TVs, telephones, and recorders, and has reported an average 40
percent increase of exports over the last few years. Guangzhou
Shipyard International Co., Ltd. manufactures ships, containers,
and large port facilities. 
</P>
