<HEADLINE> Hoddle to Extend Contract with FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Glenn Hoddle is set to be
offered a two-year extension to his contract as England coach.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle is due to meet the Football Association's International
Committee today with his future yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
England have lost three of their last four games and Hoddle
has been widely criticised for his controversial World Cup diary.
</P>
<P>
And he has been linked with the managerial vacancy at his
former club Tottenham.
</P>
<P>
But FA chief executive Graham Kelly is confident Hoddle will
complete the job and lead England to Euro 2000: "I don't think
Glenn will walk away. As he has said he has a contract and I
don't see him walking away from that contract under any
circumstances."
</P>
<P>
Hoddle will face questions from the FA about both his recent
book and the use of Eileen Drewery as the national squad's "faith
healer".
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure the book will be discussed. It has contributed to a
general climate that is unfortunate," The Daily Telegraph quoted
Kelly as saying.
</P>
<P>
Paul Ince's sending off during the disappointing 2-1 defeat by
Sweden earlier this month will also be discussed by the
International Committee.
</P>
<P>
Ince appeared to make a V-sign to England assistant manager
John Gorman when he was ordered off in Stockholm -- and Kelly and
his colleagues are now demanding Hoddle "impose discipline" on
the team.
</P>
<P>
"Sendings-off occur but what happened afterwards was not
acceptable," Kelly added.
</P>
<P>
"Ince said he made a gesture to John Gorman. That, at best, is
not acceptable. I've made it perfectly clear and Glenn
understands this. I have told him this has to be dealt with,
ideally by saying to Ince it mustn't happen again, " he said.
</P>
