<HEADLINE> Angola Worries Over Its Privatization Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos has expressed deep worry over national enterprises'
competitiveness in the process of privatization.
</P>
<P>
"National enterprises have taken up strategic positions in
government's privatization policies. However, in reality,
Angolan enterprises have been excluded, leaving foreign companies
in the limelight," the president made the remarks Thursday at a
mass gathering in Ongiva, capital city of the southern Cunene
Province, to mark the "National Hero Day", according to Friday's
O Journal de Angola.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos attributed the situation to lack of local support
in loans on the part of national enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Most of the foreign companies now operating in Angola have
strong back-up by banks in their own countries, therefore they
enjoy much more advantages than local private companies in
bidding for the purchase of national enterprises, according to
the president.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos appealed to Angolan banks for necessary loans for
national enterprises, otherwise, he warned, "the national economy
will be in the hands of foreign enterprises in the near future."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the president said the establishment of joint
ventures with foreign companies would also be a fine solution to
the problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
