<HEADLINE> Slightly-Improved Air Quality Recorded in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The air quality of some major
Chinese cities have slightly improved over the past week,
according to the China Environment Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
The center's latest air quality report indicated the air
quality in Lanzhou, Hohhot, Taiyuan and Chongqing have recorded
light air pollution from September 11 to 17, compared with the
moderate pollution over the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Tianjin, Xi'an, Guangzhou and other four cities have
also been suffering from light air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The sulphur dioxide is the major pollutant in Chongqing while
nitrogen-dioxide and suspended particles are blamed as the major
pollutants for Beijing, Guangzhou and the nine other cities, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The air quality in Guilin, Fuzhou, Zhuhai cities has risen from
the second degree to the first degree over the past week, which is
the best among the five degrees of air quality. Shantou, Wenzhou,
Xiamen and other six cities have kept their air quality at the
first degree.
</P>
<P>
The air quality in Guiyang, Yinchuan, Kunming and other 20
cities belong to the second degree, with the nitrogen-dioxide as
the major pollutant for Shanghai, Hefei and Wuhan, the sulphur
dioxide for Guiyang and the suspended particles for other cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
