</P>
<P>
With the king's approval, the Armed Forces of Thailand have
completed the annual reshuffle, which involves 522 posts.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Surayudh and Gen. Thira will replace Army
Commander-in-Chief Chetta Thanajaro and Navy Commander-in-Chief
Suwatchai Kasemsuk respectively, who will both retire in October.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of Gen. Surayudh as the new army
commander-in-chief is said to be a result of compromise.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Bangkok Post newspaper quoted an army
source as saying that Gen. Chetta's decision to name Gen. Surayudh
as his successor was made after consulting Supreme Commander Gen.
Mongkol Ampornpisit and Defense Minister and Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Surayudh, an army specialist, is a Chulachomklao Royal
Military Academy graduate.
</P>
<P>
If he stays on as commander-in-chief until he retires in 2003,
he would be Thailand's longest-serving army chief.
</P>
<P>
However, he has said before that he would stay in the job for
only three years before taking another post, possibly the supreme
commander. 
