<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
slightly higher Friday, but was bumped off its earlier intraday
highs due to the worsening crisis in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Problems with the Japanese government attempting to pass
legislation for its banking sector contributed to increased
selling of the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
It was not helped during the session by increased buying of the
U.S. dollar against the yen after the speech earlier this week by
U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, dismissing
suggestions of an interest rate cut in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the session at 59.12 U.S. cents,
up from 58.97 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Senior manager of foreign exchange at Rothschild Australia Paul
Macarounas said the currency held up reasonably well in the face
of strong selling.
</P>
<P>
He said the market saw a range of 58.95 and 59.47 U.S. cents
and expected the Australian dollar to trade between 58.85 and
59.45 overnight.
</P>
<P>
Japanese political parties are trying to reach an agreement on
bills covering a clean-up of Japan's debt-ridden banking system.
</P>
<P>
Despite complaints from the opposition, Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi hopes to have an agreement before he meets U.S. President
Bill Clinton on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Macarounas said the currency market was still circumspect in
the medium term, mindful that the Asian crisis has yet to fully
impact the market.
</P>
<P>
"The market is still not convinced that all is rosy and is
still very concerned about world growth and the effect on
commodities and the Australian dollar," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the close here the local currency was trading at 78.08
Japanese yen from 79.34 and 1.0012 German marks from 0.9942.
</P>
</TEXT>
