<HEADLINE> SADC Slammed for Rejecting U.S. Trade Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) --The Zambia Association of
Manufacturers (ZAM) has criticized the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) for rejecting the proposed U.S.
trade policy with Africa.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Times of Zambia Thursday, which was
published Friday, ZAM Chairman Mark O'Donnell said that he felt
strange that the grouping decided to reject the U.S. trade policy
with Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the economic forum of the southern African states held last
week in Mauritius, ministers from the 14 SADC states rejected the
proposed U.S. trade-not-aid policy toward Africa, saying that the
region still needs aid for development.
</P>
<P>
He said Africans should note that the donor community was now
getting fed up with giving Africa cash handouts.
</P>
<P>
It was through trade that African countries would create more
wealth and jobs and not by being perpetual recipients of aid,
said O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
He observed that donor aid was demeaning as well as enslaving
the continent and, therefore, it is time for regional groupings
to adopt strategies which would create more wealth and jobs for
Africans to develop.
</P>
<P>
The ZAM chairman also cautioned that rejecting the idea that a
trade-not-aid policy toward Africa would just compel the donor
community to stop helping the continent.
</P>
<P>
The continent would become even poorer if it would continue
depending on aid from the donor community because aid would not
bring about sustainable economic development, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade policy toward Africa, first outlined by U.S.
President Bill Clinton on his African tour earlier this year, is
designed to lessen Africa's dependence on aid money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
