<HEADLINE> Manufacturers' Orders-on-Hand for HK Decrease in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The value of manufacturers'
orders-on-hand for local production in July 1998 decreased by 14
percent over a year earlier, according to the provisional results
of a monthly survey released Friday by the Census and Statistics
Department of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Comparing July 1998 with July 1997, decreases in the value of
orders were recorded in the electrical products industry (37
percent), the plastic products industry (26 percent), the
electronic products industry (24 percent), the fabricated metal
products industry (10 percent), the textiles industry (8 percent)
and the wearing apparel industry (4 percent).
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, a slight increase in the value of orders was
recorded in the printing and publishing industry (2 percent).
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman noted that the value of
orders-on-hand for most of the industries in the manufacturing
sector remained slack in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Monthly Survey of Orders-on-hand covers a sample of some
300 manufacturing firms engaging 50 or more workers.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers' orders-on-hand refer to orders and parts of
orders received earlier by manufacturers for local production
which remain unfilled as at the end of the reference month. Orders
received by traders not engaged in production are included if such
orders are further placed to manufacturers for production
locally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
