<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Slammed for Rejecting U.S. Trade Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) --The Zambia Association of
Manufacturers (ZAM) has criticized the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) for rejecting the proposed U.S.
trade policy with Africa.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Times of Zambia Thursday, which was
published Friday, ZAM Chairman Mark O'Donnell said that he felt
strange that the grouping decided to reject the U.S. trade policy
with Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the economic forum of the southern African states held last
week in Mauritius, ministers from the 14 SADC states rejected the
proposed U.S. trade-not-aid policy toward Africa, saying that the
region still needs aid for development.
</P>
<P>
He said Africans should note that the donor community was now
getting fed up with giving Africa cash handouts.
</P>
<P>
It was through trade that African countries would create more
wealth and jobs and not by being perpetual recipients of aid,
said O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
He observed that donor aid was demeaning as well as enslaving
the continent and, therefore, it is time for regional groupings
to adopt strategies which would create more wealth and jobs for
Africans to develop.
</P>
<P>
The ZAM chairman also cautioned that rejecting the idea that a
trade-not-aid policy toward Africa would just compel the donor
community to stop helping the continent.
</P>
<P>
The continent would become even poorer if it would continue
depending on aid from the donor community because aid would not
bring about sustainable economic development, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade policy toward Africa, first outlined by U.S.
President Bill Clinton on his African tour earlier this year, is
designed to lessen Africa's dependence on aid money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Prospects for Irish-Chinese Trade: Irish Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Ireland wishes to develop
long-term trade relations with China and increase trade and
investment in this giant and growing market, Irish Minister of
International Trade Tom Kitt said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"While the trade figures between Ireland and China are not
strong enough, which we must improve, we do see the prospects,
particularly in the software area," he said. Ireland is the second
largest software exporter in the world, second only to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Kitt was speaking at a ceremony, which marked the completion of
Phase One of the Year 2000 upgrade program for the Water Supplies
Department (WSD) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR).
</P>
<P>
Irish company Datac Control International, which had been
supplying the SAR department with related software products,
presented a Year 2000 Compliance Certificate to WSD.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the recent Asian crises, the China market to us is a
very good and stable one. We see potentials in developing
long-term relations with China, which has an eight percent annual
growth in economy and low inflation rate," Kitt said.
</P>
<P>
The Irish businessmen accompanying Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern on his on-going visit to China had developed very positive
results in their discussions with their Chinese counterparts, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are excited about this market and plan to intensify our
efforts here and increase trade and investment here, and I believe
that there is tremendous scope for Irish companies to contribute
to the continued modernization of China's economy and further step
up our already vibrant business links in Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our trade with Hong Kong has been very strong and a
substantial part of our export last year to China was actually
with Hong Kong, and we are very anxious to develop further," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
