<HEADLINE> Charity Match to Be Played For Injured French Policeman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 18 (Xinhua)-- Former French and German
football stars will show up in a charity match on Sunday in a bid
to raise fund for a French policeman seriously injured by
hooligans during the France World Cup this summer.
</P>
<P>
Aime Jacquet, who resigned as France's coach after his team's
World Cup win, and FIFA president Joseph Blatter will attend the
game.
</P>
<P>
Organisers will stage the charity match in the German town of
Kehl, expecting to raise over 30,000 pounds (around 45,000
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ex-German striker Dieter Muller hoped the event would erase
the memory of "this sad affair".
</P>
<P>
Daniel Nivel, a 43-year-old French policeman, had spent six
weeks in a coma after being clubbed and kicked by a group of
German right-wing hooligans in Lens on June 21.
</P>
<P>
He has partially recovered but is still undergoing treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
