<HEADLINE> Pak Ambassador to Kabul to Bring Five Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Ambassador to
Kabul
Aziz Khan will proceed to Kandhar Saturday to bring five Iranian
Prisoners to Islamabad, Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen about his day-long visit to Tehran Thursday,
Aziz said he had informed Iranian Vice President Hasan Habibi that
as a result of personal intervention of the Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, the Afghan
Taliban had agreed to release five of the Iranian prisoners held
by them.
</P>
<P>
On their arrival, the prisoners will be handed over to the
Iranian authorities, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Habibi express appreciation for Pakistan's
efforts in this regard, particularly those of Prime Minister
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the exact number of Iranian prisoners kept by the
Taliban, Aziz said their exact number are not known. However, it
has been reported earlier that the number of prisoners may be
about 50.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aziz also said that Prime Minister Sharif will meet
Iranian President Muhammad Khattami during his stay in New York.
Sharif is scheduled to leave for New York Saturday to attend the
U.N. General Assembly Meeting.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that during his visit to Tehran he could not meet
President Khattami as he was out of the city.
</P>
<P>
He said he held an hour-long meeting with Vice President
Habibi, and delivered him a message of Nawaz Sharif for President
Khattami. 
</P>
