<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Proposes Pakistan-Iran Commission on Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz said Friday that Pakistan is ready to establish a
commission with Iran to determine the nature and level of external
interference in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after his one-day visit to Iran
Thursday, Aziz said Pakistan is ready to work closely with Iran at
the United Nations, the Organization of Islamic Conference or any
other forum to resolve the present crisis between Iran and
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Iranian officials, Aziz emphasized that
"it is most important to defuse the prevailing tension that has
been created by the massing of Iranian troops along the Afghan
border."
</P>
<P>
"A conflict would have a devastating effect on the peace and
stability of the entire region and should be avoided at all cost,"
the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that the purpose of his visit was to have frank and
intensive deliberations on the situation in Afghanistan and to
discuss measures that would lead to an easing of the tension
between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said he was satisfied with the outcome of the visit. "It
provided a welcome opportunity to have detailed discussions on
matters of mutual concern in an atmosphere of cordiality."
</P>
<P>
He, however, told reporters that the Iranian leadership
repeated their outrage at the killing of their personnel in the
northern Afghan town of Mazar-i-Sharif and reiterated their demand
that the Taliban should render an apology for the killing,
apprehend and extradite to Iran those responsible and repatriate
the bodies of the remaining personnel killed.
</P>
<P>
Aziz noted that the Iranian side also expressed concern over
the reports of large-scale killing in the central Afghan province
of Bamyan and Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Iran again alleged that the recent Taliban victories were
possible only due to Pakistan's military support and assistance,
according to the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that he told the Iranian leaders that "we do not
accept their allegations that our armed forces had been involved
in the Taliban military operations. This was completely untrue."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed that Pakistan's relations with
Iran are "precious" to it. "Pakistan is determined not to allow
the current situation to harm these abiding ties," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Guiding HK Into Tech-Driven Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Over the past six months,
Tien Chang-lin, former president of University of California,
Berkeley, USA, has shuttled between the west coast of America and
Hong Kong on a journey to explore a way out for Hong Kong's
flagging industry by injecting high technology.
</P>
<P>
That is a task Tien, now professor of engineering at Berkeley,
charged himself with in March this year when he accepted Hong
Kong's Executive Chief Tung Chee Hwa's invitation to chair the
Commission on Innovation and Technology.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Professor Tien said:
"For Hong Kong, the most important (thing) is to develop
high-value-added industries."
</P>
<P>
In his view, there are two categories of high-value-added
industries. First, innovated methods or improved technology can
help traditional industries, like toy-making and electronics, to
increase added value of the products.
</P>
<P>
But merely industrial upgrading is not enough, Tien noted. Hong
Kong needs to develop high-value-added frontier industries of the
21st century, such as biotech, telecommunications and new
materials.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's economy has transformed from manufacturing-based to
service-oriented over the past two decades because of the massive
shift of factories to southern China. Professor Tien said that
the economy base is too narrow to cushion itself from external
shocks like the Asia financial storm.
</P>
<P>
To be well positioned for the challenges of the knowledge-based
21st century, Hong Kong needs to promote innovation and technology
and engage in high-value-added activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The key (problem) for Hong Kong is that it has no overall
scheme of technology development; it has academic facilities,
technological center and science park, but all done piecemeal,"
said Professor Tien, who is also an adviser on the development of
Silicon Valley, the very epitome of high technology hub in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Tien said that his commission will take in experiences of
success and lessons of failure from other places, like Singapore,
Taiwan and South Korea, in drawing up Hong Kong's blueprint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Guiding HK Into Tech-Driven Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He set store by the role of government, which he said should
not intervene directly in the operation of a certain industry, but
needs to invest in physical, human and technology infrastructure
to create an environment conducive to innovation and technology
development and commercialization.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has one of the world's highest GDP per capita, but
its input in research and development (RD) only accounts for 0.2
to 0.3 percent of its GDP, far below the global average of two to
three percent. Besides, Hong Kong is a place with no RD
center. "This is an anomaly," said Tien.
</P>
<P>
He said what the government can do right now is to foster a
midstream research and development institution. "Without this
link, Hong Kong is unable to attract and accommodate talent;
without talent, innovation and technology can never come forth,"
said Tien. "The top priority is to absorb, reserve and develop
talented people."
</P>
<P>
Tien also stressed that Hong Kong must build up strong
partnership with the mainland in technology development and
application.
</P>
<P>
He was deeply impressed with a three-day trip to the Pearl
River Delta in southern China last weekend, saying: "The prospect
for cooperation between the two places is marvelous. In the
future, Hong Kong and the Pearl River Delta will not only be a
financial, trade, information and operation center, but may become
a high-tech industrial hub."
</P>
<P>
Some suggestions, which can be implemented immediately, will be
put forward in an interim report the commission is to submit to
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa by the end of this month, according
to Tien.
</P>
<P>
Other suggestions that need further deliberation will be left
to a final report to be handed in no later than June next year.
</P>
<P>
"This is really an urgent business," Tien said. "We must seize
every minute and second in the fast changing market economy."
</P>
<P>
"I'm optimistic about the future despite the current economic
trouble," he said. "That's why I accept the job." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Meets Visiting Irish Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa reaffirmed Hong Kong's commitment to free market here Friday
when meeting with visiting Prime Minister of Ireland Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
"We have a flexible market which allows very efficient price
adjustment for major production factors. We are aware that it is
necessary to allow market forces to bring our prices to a level at
which the market can afford. We are ready to take the pain arising
from the adjustment process," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
There has been immediate and huge adjustment in the property
market, Tung said, adding the adjustment process has been
extremely efficient.
</P>
<P>
"The labor market has also been undergoing adjustment, but this
will take some time," he told Ahern. Speaking from his former life
as a businessman, Tung pointed out that "employers must be caring
to their employees in the adjustment process in order to bring the
best out of their employees."
</P>
<P>
Ahern congratulated Tung on the successful implementation of
the "One Country, Two Systems" principle as the Special
Administrative Region is stepping into its second year after
returning to China. The prime minister believed that with
efficient market system the Hong Kong economy would rebound
quickly.
</P>
<P>
Tung told Ahern that with huge reserves and in the absence of
foreign debts, Hong Kong would continue to invest heavily in
education and infrastructure, and capitalize on its links with the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Irish investors are welcome to participate in the city's
infrastructure projects, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We are the most international city in Asia and are determined
to remain that way. We welcome investors to participate in our
developments from all over the world," Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
Ahern arrived in Hong Kong Thursday following a visit to the
Chinese mainland and will be leaving tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
