<HEADLINE> China Names Top Ten Environmental Protection Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The State General
Administration of Environmental Protection today named the
10 cities which made the best contributions to environmental
protection in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The 10 cities -- Guilin, Shantou, Haikou, Chengdu, Ningbo,
Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Suzhou, Yantai and Beijing -- were selected
from among 46 key coastal, opened and tourist cities, according to
an official with the State General Administration of Environmental
Protection.
</P>
<P>
The final selection was based on assessment of their
environmental quality, pollution control, as well as environmental
construction and management, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Four cities -- Zhuhai, Shenzhen, Xiamen and Dalian -- have been
named state model environmental protection cities, and they were
not part of this selection.
</P>
<P>
The State General Administration of Environmental Protection
today also made public details of the environmental assessment of
the 46 cities. Shantou, Chengdu, Zhanjiang, Wenzhou, Guilin,
Lianyungang, Yantai, Ningbo, Beihai and Nanchang ranked as the
cities with the best environmental quality.
</P>
<P>
Changsha and Shanghai have been most successful in controlling
pollution. Guilin and Nanjing performed best in environmental
construction, while Shantou and Haikou were the top two cities in
environmental management.
</P>
<P>
The official said China's major cities attached more importance
to and made more investment in the environmental protection last
year.
</P>
<P>
For example, Beijing has instituted a motor vehicle emissions
control program, and also plans to invest 27 billion yuan (3.3
billion U.S. dollars) to improve the city's air quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
