<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Finish Down But Off Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- An one-and-a-half hour delay
before the Australian sharemarket opened Friday meant investors
took a positive lead from Japan, keeping the losses on the local
bourse to a minimum, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The local market was slightly lower at the close with the all
ordinaries index ending 2.9 points, or 0.11 percent, down at
2,539.9, off a low of 2,525.6 and a high of 2,542.8.
</P>
<P>
Problems with the electronic automatic trading system stalled
the start to around 11:30 local time, but Japan was already off
its lows as was trading in the September share price index futures
contract and the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, investors switched attention from the overnight
falls on northern hemisphere stock exchanges, particularly Wall
Street, and concentrated on Japan, where Thursday the Nikkei 225
contributed to a lower close on the all ordinaries.
</P>
<P>
"Japan had already gone down by the time trading started here,"
Peter Struk of Reynolds &AMP; Co. said.
</P>
<P>
"Our futures were also a lot stronger at that point and our
dollar was picking up, so it was becoming positive before we had
even opened."
</P>
<P>
Doubts of a worldwide cut in interest rates to arrest a global
economic decline fed into the banking sector, forcing the all
industrials index to close down 9.9 points at 4,461.4.
</P>
<P>
Despite weaker base metal prices, stronger oil and gold bullion
prices helped the all resources index to finish in positive
territory, rising 3.8 points to 990.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was lackluster on a volume of 234.84 million
shares traded at a value of 790.31 million Australian dollars
(474.18 million U.S. dollars), with 475 falls, 369 rises and 324
stocks steady.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume was Coca-Cola Beverages with a turnover of 36.76
million shares.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Coca Cola Amatil, facing a multi-million dollar
compensation claim in the courts from former chief executive Norb
Cole, fell 7.5 cents, or 1.61 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gained 26.2 points, 2.62 percent, to 1,026.4.
Gold bullion closed 3.35 higher at 290.40 U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto gained five cents and WMC was up 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
Among the banks, National Australia Bank was up 1.9 cents,
Westpac dipped 1.4 cents, ANZ dropped 30, or 3.28 percent and
Commonwealth Bank fell 20.2, or 1.03 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
