<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stays Firm in Safeguarding Macao's Social Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian
Qichen today reiterated China's firm commitment to support and
cooperate with the Macao government in its efforts to curb
rising crimes in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the third plenary meeting of the Preparatory
Committee for the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) that
opened in Beijing today, Qian, who is also chairman of the
Preparatory Committee, said that Macao is still facing challenges
in maintaining public security order and that the Central
Government will closely watch the situation in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"There is no change in the stance and determination of the
Central Government to help safeguard Macao's social stability,"
the vice premier said, adding that Portuguese Macao authorities
should take full responsibility for local public security before
Macao returns to China in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier expressed his appreciation for what
the four work groups under the Preparatory Committee have achieved
over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The group in charge of administrative affairs held
advice-seeking meetings between September 3-6 in Macao to solicit
opinions from people of various sectors about how to form the
Selection Committee for the first Macao SAR government.
</P>
<P>
This is the first activity ever staged by the Preparatory
Committee in Macao, which is democratic and open, and has
increased the understanding and exchange between the Preparatory
Committee and the general public.
</P>
<P>
It has also enhanced the Macao people's awareness of
participating in political and government affairs, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
The legal group has completed the preliminary review of 135
laws of those being enacted in Macao by the Portuguese authorities.
</P>
<P>
The economic group has studied local financial issues including
pension payment for civil servants and fiscal reserve, and the
social and cultural group has held extensive discussions about the
arrangement of public holidays in the region in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Qian praised the generous donations by people in Macao to
flooding areas in Chinese inland areas this summer, saying their
acts testify to the saying that "blood is thicker than water."
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting heard the reports by four groups on their work
progress and examined three draft resolutions concerning setting
up Independent Commission Against Corruption, auditing office and
customs office in the future Macao SAR; the pension payment for
civil servants and public holidays arrangements in the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
