<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Rejects Belgrade's Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- German officials Friday rejected
a protest by Belgrade over a statement by German Defense Minister
Volker Ruehe on the Kosovo crisis, saying that Germany will in no
way support separatist and terrorist activities in the Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government Thursday strongly protested what it
called an "aggressive statement which openly threatens to launch
military attacks on the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Ruehe in an interview with the German
ZDF television network Tuesday evening, during which the defense
minister said that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
could launch a military strike against Kosovo within three to five
weeks if attacks on civilians continued there.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Yugoslav Tanjug news agency, the
Yugoslav government lodged a protest with German charge d'affaires
Rolf Krause at the Foreign Ministry in Belgrade Thursday,
describing Ruehe's statement as a naked support for the Kosovo
separatists and terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The German news agency DPA Friday quoted German Foreign
Ministry officials as saying that Ruehe had spoken only within the
context of a NATO debate on a possible military intervention in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
German officials noted that Bonn had also made efforts to
prevent the Kosovo armed rebels, the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA),
from getting financial support from Kosovo-Albanians living in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel was also criticized by
Belgrade in the protest which reportedly said that the sanctions
against Belgrade advocated by Kinkel had destabilized the
situation in the Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
