<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Troops to Stay in DRC: Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Namibia has confirmed that
its troops, along with troops from Angola and Zimbabwe, would remain
in the war-torn Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) until the
situation there had stabilized.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said Thursday during his stopover in
Zimbabwe that the allied forces would help train the DRC army to deal
with future invasions after the conflict, South African Press
Association reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking in Harare after an hour-long meeting with
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe during a stopover on his way home
from a two-day state visit to Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
"We want peace in the region so that we can concentrate on building
our economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, Angola and Zimbabwe sent troops to the DRC last month to
help President Laurent Kabila crush rebels, who started an uprising on
August 2 to overthrow the DRC government.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said other African countries from outside the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) had expressed their willingness
to help Kabila in his fight against the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said he and Mugabe also discussed developments in Lesotho,
where allegations of electoral fraud have given rise to unrest, as
well as bilateral relations between their countries.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports that some Namibian opposition parties were
agitating for the Caprivi Strip of Namibia to become part of Botswana,
the two leaders said they hoped the dispute would be solved amicably.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
