<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Big Australian Parties Cautious About Mixed Polling Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian ruling parties
and the opposition party remain cautious during their election
campaign with latest opinion poll showing mixed results.
</P>
<P>
Despite optimistic claims by commentators and analysts that
Prime Minister John Howard is expected to be re-elected, recent
opinion polls suggest a tight contest.
</P>
<P>
An AC Nielsen poll published Friday in Melbourne-based
newspaper The Age and the Sydney Morning Herald has found the
Australian Labor Party, the opposition party, in front at 52
percent on a two party preferred vote, with the ruling Australian
Liberal and National Party coalition lagging four percent behind
on 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
But exactly the opposite result was found in a Morgan telephone
poll out Friday which put the coalition ahead on 52 percent and
Labor behind on 48 percent. Both polls were taken at the start of
the week.
</P>
<P>
A second Morgan poll, taken on a face-to-face basis last
weekend, found the Labor Party at 55 percent compared with the
coalition on 45 percent on a two party preferred basis.
</P>
<P>
The coalition had led the Labor Party in opinion polls during
the first two weeks until September 15, when the nation's leading
newspaper The Australian reported 44 percent polled supported the
Labor, two percentage points ahead of the coalition in the latest
Newspoll.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the polling result, Opposition Leader
Kim Beazley said he would wait for the final poll, adding a shift
to the Labor didn't necessarily indicate the Labor would win
seats.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press said the Newspoll has the best
record of predicting election results.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard last Friday acknowledged that the
election would be a tight one after he was asked to comment on an
AC Nielsen poll showing support for the Labor dropped 3 points to
39 percent while the coalition remained steady on 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
His cautious attitude proved right Friday as the latest poll
found a surge in voter hostility to the government-proposed goods
and services tax (GST), the central piece of the government's tax
reform plan.
</P>
<P>
The Australia Democrats Party, which are widely expected to
hold the balance of power if the ruling coalition won the October
3 election, Friday declared their partial opposition to GST,
saying food should be exempted from taxation under the proposed
GST.
</P>
<P>
A report released Friday by four academics of Australia
Institute said imposing a 10 percent GST on food was unfair and
would hit poorer Australians the hardest.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party, which have been focusing their attack against
the GST and accusing the tax plan of being unfair to low-income
earners, are expected to beef up their attack in the final two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Party lost the 1993 federal election because
Australian voters feared introduction of a GST proposed by the
Liberal Party would lead to price hikes, and in the 1996 election
Howard vowed "never ever" to introduce a GST.
</P>
<P>
In order to win the support of voters, both sides are so far
being extra careful about the campaign.
</P>
<P>
For the Howard camp, the key election strategy is caution and
discipline even before the election campaign began.
</P>
<P>
Howard has been careful to manage his public appearances to
limit any chance of having his message obscured by careless
mistakes or images of protests.
</P>
<P>
His camp's caution has extended to the traveling media group,
with details of the coming day's events mostly kept top secret
until only a few hours before the prime minister starts his day.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Howard has pushed the twin themes of his
campaign: the need for tax reform to provide revenue growth to
fund essential services, and his economic record which he says
makes him best qualified to run the economy in the face of the
Asian meltdown.
</P>
<P>
The Labor face an arduous task to defeat the coalition in this
election, since it must win 27 seats more than it holds at present
to gain a majority in parliament, while the coalition hold 90
seats, 15 seats more than the required half of the 148 seats in
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
