<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Wants Currency Trade on WTO Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
considering asking the World Trade Organization (WTO) to include
currency trade on its agenda and the Planning Commission will
formulate proposals for the purpose, a government official said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
India is justified in lobbying for a global mechanism to
control currency trade in light of the Asian crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There was earlier a proposal to impose some kind of levy on
currency trade. We could ask the international community to revive
the proposal or ask the WTO to regulate currency movement in the
same manner as it does with commodities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"An attempt has been made to introduce a modicum of fairness in
the trade of commodities. But trade in currency remains free from
any restraint. Currency markets work 24 hours a day. There are no
international agreements on currency trade," he further said.
</P>
</TEXT>
