<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WMO Regional Association Elects New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Meteorological
Organization's (WMO's) fifth regional association has elected Lim
Joo Tick of Malaysia as its new president for the 1998-2002
period, replacing Dr. Karjoto of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Lim beat rival John R. Lumpsden of New Zealand in the 12th
conference of the Regional Association V (Southwest Pacific) of
the WMO in Denpasar, Bali of Indonesia, on Friday, according to
Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Sri Diharto of Indonesia has been elected as vice president.
</P>
<P>
WMO Secretary General Prof. P. Obashi welcomed Lim's
appointment, expressing the hope that the new leadership would be
able to harness the potentials of developing countries in the
Southwest Pacific and improve the image of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The WMO has 185 members divided into six regional associations.
</P>
<P>
The 12th conference of the Regional Association V opened Monday
and ends next Tuesday (September 22). Some 57 participants from 15
members are attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that one of the topics discussed at the
conference is the planning and realization of cooperation
involving national meteorological agencies in Regional Association
V. 
</P>
</TEXT>
