<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Successful in Reforming State-owned Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province, a leading industrial base in the country, has made
substantial progress in reforming its state-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
Vice Provincial Governor Chen Chenggao said his province has
assessed the competence of directors in 90 percent of the 1,000
large and medium-sized state-owned firms in the province.
</P>
<P>
In the course of this process, 267 incapable directors were
dismissed, while 860 competent young people were promoted.
</P>
<P>
To raise funds for further development, 24 large state-owned
firms have been listed on either the Shenzhen or Shanghai stock
Exchange, raising 12.3 billion yuan over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Over 500 large and medium-sized enterprises have cooperated
with overseas partners to build joint venture projects involving
a total contractual volume of 3.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sixty key state-owned firms have been chosen to experiment in a
series of reform measures including separating production from
service, reforming the distribution system, and introducing
a modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
On average, each of these enterprises will absorb at least 10
million U.S. dollars annually to upgrade technology.
</P>
<P>
The province offered new jobs to 139,000 laid-off workers last
year and for another 250,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
While invigorating large and key state-owned firms, Liaoning
allowed 57 percent of its smaller state firms to operate in a more
flexible way, such as merging with others or setting up joint
stock ventures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
