<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in
Tokyo Friday on a late afternoon wave of buybacks in the wake of
Nikkei index's plunge to its lowest level in 12-and-a-half years
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 123.98 points, or 0.89
percent, from Thursday's close, to end at 13,983.12.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 4.16 points or 0.39 percent to
1,073.22.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section rose to an estimated 453 million
shares from Thursday's 411.73 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan led all shares in volume for the
fourth straight day.
</P>
<P>
Investors sought refuge in food and beverage, pharmaceutical
and other issues, which are seen as more resilient against Japan's
slumping economy.
</P>
<P>
Construction, petroleum and steel shares also advanced despite
their poor earnings forecast, hinting that government-linked
pension funds bought stocks in order to support the market, trader
said.
</P>
<P>
Most big-name exporters, however, fell after the New York and
London stock markets were hit hard Thursday due to fears over a
diminishing global economy, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,341 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 750 to 400, with 138 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
