<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Detained Kampala Mayor Denied Bail Again in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Mayor of Ugandan capital
Kampala Nasser Sebaggala has been denied bail a second time by
the Massachusetts district court of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The ruling came out after a 90-minute hearing late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the court is considering relaxing the conditions for
his release and the trial may take place in October, the New
Vision newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new terms, the embattled mayor has to declare before
the U.S. federal authorities all his assets and bank accounts as
a precondition for the new bail application.
</P>
<P>
Robert Wolf, the presiding judge of the court, was quoted as
saying that he was not satisfied with the 5,000-U.S.-Dollar bail
bond to guarantee the mayor's return to the U.S. for trial if he
was allowed to return to Kampala this time.
</P>
<P>
But he asked both the defense lawyers and the prosecution to
come up with a new set of conditions which might be useful for
the mayor's release.
</P>
<P>
The defense lawyers also asked for removal of the electronic
bracelet tied onto Sebaggala, saying that it inconvenienced the
mayor so much that it hindered him from performing religious
rites.
</P>
<P>
Before the hearing, the presiding judge received a petition
signed by over 8,000 Ugandans urging for the release of their
mayor.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution, led by Theordore Chuag, opposed the five-page
document, arguing that it abuses the U.S. judicial system.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala, who was elected mayor of Kampala in April, 1998,
was arrested in New York in mid-June for making false customs
declarations and using false checks in a Boston bank.
</P>
<P>
He was reported to have gone to attend an international
meeting in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Since his arrest, his opponents back home have accused him of
being without an A level certificate required of this post and
demanded his stepping down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many of his supporters have made a loud cry to the
Ugandan government, calling for helping this mayor out. The long
document bearing their signatures is their latest effort toward
the eventual release of the mayor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
