<HEADLINE> Lusaka Court Threatens to Release Coup Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Lusaka High Court Judge
Japhet Banda has threatened to release all the 79 treason
suspects in connection with last year's foiled military coup on
constitutional bail if the state does not decongest prisons.
</P>
<P>
Banda made the threat in an interview here Thursday, the
government-owned Times of Zambia said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The judge said that he would gave the state up to 14:30 local
time Friday to explain why it was not looking into what he termed
the "poor state" of prisons failure to which he would release the
suspects on bail under the powers vested in him by the country's
criminal procedure code and the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"The court can take drastic action if the state does not want
to listen to what I have said about decongesting prisons," Banda
said, adding that he has got powers to give the suspects
constitutional bail even in a treason trial.
</P>
<P>
An irate Banda said he did not want the suspects to die in
prison as he would "not try corpses."
</P>
<P>
He indicated that a report presented to the court by doctors
who conducted medical examination on the suspects at a
Lusaka-based military hospital, disclosed that many suspects were
suffering from respiratory infections and the only way to avoid
cross-infections is to decongest prisons.
</P>
<P>
Banda said that his visit to the prisons last month confirmed
there was congestion and he had since written to Home Affairs
Minister Peter Machungwa, advising the state to take some
suspects to other places of security as enshrined in the Zambian
laws.
</P>
<P>
The on-going trial of the 79 suspects who were charged with
treason has lasted for nearly five months. The process is
disrupted now and then since many suspects suffer different kinds
of diseases due to bad conditions in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
