<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Cancer Recovery Club Gives Patients a New Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Li Zengguang, a 61-year-old
engineer, just celebrated his tenth birthday several days ago.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to imagine that I have already lived another ten
years since I became ill," Li said with tears in his eyes at his
birthday celebration party. He was diagnosed with cancer of the
stomach ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
Li is a member of a Hangzhou cancer recovery club in east
China's Zhejiang Province. The 1,500-member club has helped many
patients prolong their lives since its establishment in March 1993.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou has a high incidence of cancer. About 3,000 people are
stricken with various kinds of cancers each year there, and about
2,000 die from the disease. The club is the third of its kind in
China, along with those in Shanghai and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"It is the club and all of you, my dear friends, that have
inspired me to fight against the deadly disease.I will treasure my
new life," Li passionately told the club members.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Jiapeng, the club's secretary-general said Mondays,
Wednesdays, and Fridays are the days they meet to consult with
each other and foster mutual confidence.
</P>
<P>
While the members take their prescribed medical treatments, the
club also organizes psychotherapy, holds lectures on how to fight
against cancer, and provides opportunities to exchange feelings
and experiences.
</P>
<P>
"Cancer does not necessarily lead to death. Besides medical
treatment, optimism is another important factor in conquering the
disease. We should be confident that we will win the battle," said
Wang Tingying, a club member who has been fighting against cancer
of the bladder for more than ten years.
</P>
<P>
Research on 201 cancer patients jointly conducted by the club
and Zhejiang Medical University in 1997 showed that club members
appeared more optimistic and lived longer than other patients.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Min, a club leader, said people from all walks of
life are paying more and more attention to them. And the city
government offered them a special fund earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
He said membership is always on the rise, and many of the
members have taken the club as their second home.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best to help my fellow club members out of
suffering, and make the club a cosy home for all of them," said
Yuan Min, a terminal cancer patient who has lived another five
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
