<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grain Prices Will Not Skyrocket  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China's grain prices will not
skyrocket though they have been rising recently, and are expected
to rise further in the next few months, predicted an official of
the State Development Planning Commission here today.
</P>
<P>
"China has the ability to maintain grain prices at a rational
level," said Bi Jingquan, director of the Price Management
Department of the Commission.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "the severe flooding China suffered this summer
will not affect grain production too much."
</P>
<P>
Grain output "is expected to reach the planned amount of 492.5
billion kilograms, or slightly less," according to the Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China still has sufficient grain reserves of 200
billion kilograms, and an expected abundant international grain
supply will also set a strong foundation for a stable grain
market in China, Bi said.
</P>
<P>
In August, the price of rice rose in certain major cities in
the north and northeast, according to the China Price Information
Center. But later statistics show that prices have been kept
stable or have even gone down in some cities in early September.
</P>
<P>
Bi attributed the rising prices mainly to the floods, which
affected the grain supply in flood-stricken areas and brought
diminished market expectation for people in other areas.
</P>
<P>
"They believe floods will inevitably raise grain prices, but
this is not always the case," Bi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
