<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Fall at This Week's Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian wool prices
dropped again by an average 2 percent at auctions this week,
taking the price falls to 15 percent over the nine weeks of the
selling season to date, the Australian Council of Wool Exporters
(ACWE) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In its weekly market report ACWE said the eastern market
indicator declined by 10 cents to end the week at 517 Australian
cents per kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
A total of 101,571 bales were offered with 14.5 percent passed
in, comprising 9.8 percent in Sydney, 11.3 percent in Melbourne
and 22.9 percent in Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
ACWE said the market was still dull and suffering badly from
lack of demand.
</P>
<P>
"There was better tone and a bit more confidence in the sale
rooms as the week progressed, reflecting increased interest from a
wider range of customers overseas, but it does need to be kept in
mind that we are talking about the lowest price levels seen for
the last four and a half years in Australian currency terms," ACWE
said.
</P>
<P>
It said many exporters continued to be plagued by contract
defaults with the problem now evident in an increasing number of
markets.
</P>
<P>
In its weekly report Wesfarmers Dalgety, one of Australia's
leading farm produce traders, said the wool prices went down
further this week after the biggest weekly offering of the season
so far hit the market but sales had stabilized by Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said the smaller quantity of 57,336 bales up for sale next
week in Newcastle and Fremantle, two coastal towns in eastern and
western Australia, should provide some support to the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
