<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grain Prices Will Not Skyrocket  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China reformed its grain marketing system beginning last May,
asking grain marketing firms to sell grain at slight profits, which
helped increased market grain prices.
</P>
<P>
China's drive against smuggling also increased prices for
edible oil, according to Bi.
</P>
<P>
The slight rise in grain prices is of positive significance, Bi
noted, adding that long-term low grain prices dampen the
enthusiasm of farmers for grain production and causes an overall
loss in the grain marketing sector.
</P>
<P>
"Even now, grain prices are below the country's demand for
slight-profit selling prices," Bi said.
</P>
<P>
Though the increase of grain prices may raise the prices of
other services and commodities, an economist from the State
Council Development and Research Center welcomed such an increase.
</P>
<P>
"It's good news for China's current economy," he said, adding
that China is facing the pressure of deflation now, as the
inflation rate has been kept negative for several months.
</P>
<P>
Analysis shows that a ten percent increase in grain prices will
directly bring the overall price index up by one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
Though this is the case, China has made efforts to prevent
grain prices from becoming too high.
</P>
<P>
The commission released a notice recently urging local
governments to adopt measures to crackdown illegal grain market
activities such as windfall profits achieved by driving up grain
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
