<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Garment Industry Attracts Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's light industry,
particularly the garment business, was the most attractive sector
to new investors seeking promotional privileges from the Board of
Investment (BOI) in August, a BOI report available Friday said.
</P>
<P>
Some 39 projects with a total investment of 11.2 billion baht
(280 million U.S. dollars) received promotional privileges in the
month, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 10 were in light industries such as textile,
garments and toys, eight in electronics and electrical appliances,
seven in chemicals, paper and plastic products, six in services,
five in metal products, machinery and equipment and three in
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Textile and garment manufacturers topped the number of
investors obtaining privileges, with projects that would create
1,266 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The industry is expected to grow further as the government has
decided to cut import tariffs on textile machinery to 5 percent
from the previous 20-30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai garments have become increasingly competitive in
higher-end markets in the United States, the European Union (EU)
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
But for middle- and low-income markets, Thai exporters face
heavy competition from lower-wage countries such as China and
India.
</P>
<P>
The report said a major obstacle textile and garment
manufacturers are facing now is an expected decrease in import
quotas from the United States and the EU.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent of the total quotas given by the United
States were used during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Another problem for manufacturers is the inability to buy raw
materials due to cash-flow problems. Many bankers are reluctant to
extend credits to exporters.
</P>
<P>
An increase in production costs due to high lending rates is
also undermining the country's competitiveness, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
