<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Online to Start Roaming E-Mail Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Africa Online, a leading
Internet service provider in Africa, will next month launch a new
e-mail service which will enable travelers to get their e-mail
messages and reply as they arrive.
</P>
<P>
This service is a response to the need among the firm's
customers for easy access to their electronic mail messages,
Africa Online's Product manager David Ochanda said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have grouped with a consortium of international service
providers, known as the Gric Alliance, through which the company
can provide a continuity of service for its customers wherever
they are," said Ochanda.
</P>
<P>
Using the so-called roaming service, people traveling abroad
will no longer live in fear of returning home to a stack of
unattended electronic mail, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Users will be able to access their accounts on their laptop
computers while still abroad.
</P>
<P>
The roaming service allows customers to dial into numbers of
Internet providers who have signed into a consortium in the
countries where they are visiting.
</P>
<P>
The service eliminates the need for international telephone
calls and minimizes chances of bad connections, cut-offs or
garbled messages, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The manager said the service is mainly designed for business
travelers who are out of the country for at least three to six
times a year, employees of international and multinational
organizations, as well as students studying abroad.
</P>
<P>
Previously, people traveling out of the reach of their service
providers, especially in Kenya, have had to suspend their
accounts for the duration of their absence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
