<HEADLINE> Zhoushan Announces Fisheries Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The city of Zhoushan in east
China's coastal Province of Zhejiang plans to vigorously expand
its fisheries sector over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to produce 1.25 million tons of aquatic products
annually by the year 2002, with the annual output value expected
to hit seven billion yuan, according to Mayor Wang Huizhong.
</P>
<P>
Wang expressed hope that science and technology will contribute
55 percent of the growth of the fisheries industry and that
related efforts will help all local fishing villages become more
affluent.
</P>
<P>
Zhoushan, a city consisting of 1,339 islets, is one of China's
major fishing grounds. The city accounts for more than 70 percent
of Zhejiang Province's total exports of aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
However, the prolonged fishing ban, shrinking fishing grounds
and the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Seas which
went into effect in China in 1996, have made it more difficult for
the city to realize its goals, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The city has decided to follow a sustainable development
strategy based on the development of fisheries and to introduce
measures to readjust the fishing structure, introduce scientific
and technological achievements to improve related operations and
develop international and domestic markets for aquatic
products. The goal is to maintain high growth for the fisheries
sector.
</P>
<P>
Zhoushan's 12,000 vessel fishing fleet produced 1.17 million
tons of aquatic products in 1997. Enitem




nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
