<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Growing Miracle On Pamirs Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- "What fine wheat!" exclaims
50-year-old farmer Muala standing in a wheat field 3,600
meters above sea level on the Pamirs Plateau, northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Muala and his fellow Tajik countrymen of Budaer Township are
joyful over the 3.33 hectares of wheat maturing on the plateau,
but they are hardly aware that they have made history by
establishing a new world's record for growing wheat at high
elevations, fully 300 meters over the old mark.
</P>
<P>
"It's a miracle in wheat-growing history. The limits were 3,000
meters to 3,300 meters above the sea level," noted Chen Xingwu, an
associate research fellow of the Academy of Agricultural Sciences
of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Budaer Township belongs to the Tajik Autonomous County of
Taxkorgan in Xinjiang, where inadequate grain has long been a
cause of poverty. This year, the county experimented with over 133
hectares of wheat with the help of plastic sheeting, all of which
were ripe with high yields recently.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the key to planting wheat at high elevations
lies in keeping in the warmth, and the plastic sheeting has proved
efficient.
</P>
<P>
But Muala seems to be little interested in the scientific
implications of the experiment. What delights him is that his 0.4
hectares of land reaped 1.8 tons of wheat, which is enough to
feed his whole family. Last year, the family only harvested one
ton of highland barley.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe the successful experiment means a lot to this
county of 28,000 people who are still living below the
national poverty line.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to expand this wheat experiment to 1,333 hectares
within two years, and bid good-bye to poverty in the new century,"
said Rozi Gulibayi, the head of the county, who is also a deputy
to the National People's Congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
