<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Victims in Inner Mongolia Well Accommodated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Inner Mongolia's last
3,000-odd flood victims who were forced to live in the open
on barren hills finally left the wilderness on Thursday and
moved into newly built housing, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Heavy flooding on Nenjiang River and its tributaries in Inner
Mongolia this summer destroyed 378,600 houses and left 344,000
people homeless.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem of flood victims living in the open air
and ensure them a safe winter, the regional government
quickly distributed flood relief funds and materials among the flood
victims who are using them to rebuild houses destroyed by the
floods.
</P>
<P>
Some 288 schools which were unable to begin classes on September 1
because of the floods had all been opened to students by September 10,
according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
