<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily and CCTV Join Hands to Supervise Government (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yu Guoming, deputy director of the Public Opinions Research
Institute of People's University, said that thanks to the joint
efforts of these two big news sources, the accuracy,
authoritativeness and timeliness of the reports are guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the cooperation is conducive to putting an
in-depth report and an on-the-spot interview together, which can
ensure that the report is more profound, vivid and soul-touching,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Lu Mingjun, a "People's Daily" reporter participating in the
joint program, noted that the media usually encounters many
obstacles created by various sectors and persons when they prepare
to criticize a government department for its wrong doing.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between several news organizations will
undoubtedly strengthen their ability to endure the pressure," he
said, explaining that this case was an typical example.
</P>
<P>
The supervision of the government by the media will be a unique
way in China for exposing official misbehaviors and criticizing
social corruption, in order to guarantee the people's democratic
rights.
</P>
<P>
This issue was raised again at the National People's Congress
this year, when many deputies called for stronger supervision of
the government by the media to eradicate corruption and ensure
that the country is governed by law.
</P>
<P>
Top Chinese leaders have recently repeatedly urged that media
watch be enhanced, particularly, cooperation between news
organizations to create a healthier social environment.
</P>
<P>
Sources revealed that "People's Daily" is conducting some
reforms, including a new column aimed at encouraging more people
to voice their views in the paper.
</P>
<P>
CCTV made some changes earlier this year to update its "Focus
Report" by including more sensitive subjects and cover a wider
range of issues.
</P>
<P>
The All-China Journalists Association established a special
committee last month to safeguard the rights of reporters and
editors and encourage them to deal with problems more boldly.
</P>
<P>
According to Professor Yu, the supervision of the government by
the media has become commonplace nationwide, and China is entering
a period of stronger confidence, freer speech and more
transparency.
</P>
<P>
"However, the media is not the solution to every problem. We
still need a more tolerant social atmosphere, as well as a more
open and law-abiding system," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
