<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Government Urged to Ban Trout Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Party, the major

opposition party in New Zealand, is proposing legislation to
overturn
a government decision to allow the importation of raw trout meat.
</P>
<P>
Wellington-based Evening Post reported Friday that the bill
would
be drafted by Mark Burton, a member of the parliament from the
Labor
Party.
</P>
<P>
The action of the Labor Party seems to be a response to
complaints
about a recent decision to lift restrictions on imported trout and

salmon, which were published Friday in The Dominion, another
Wellington-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted some New Zealand salmon farmers as saying the
decision of the New Zealand government would give Australian
exporters free rein in New Zealand markets but New Zealand salmon
farmers were banned from exporting to Australia.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand King Salmon company chief executive Paul Steere
said
the New Zealand industry generally supports free trade, but not if
it
meant "we've invited the Australians to come and play on our field

but we aren't allowed to have a return match."
</P>
<P>
It is "silly" that it is illegal to farm trout in New Zealand
but
Australian trout farmers could export trout to New Zealand to be
sold in competition with New Zealand salmon, he added.
</P>
<P>
Benmore Salmon farm manager Brian Hutton said the decision to
lift
the ban on fresh trout and salmon imports would lead to "one way
traffic" in the fresh salmon trade with Australia.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, Australia has blocked fresh salmon
exports
from New Zealand and other countries on the grounds that the fish

could introduce disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
