<HEADLINE> Overseas Tourism Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China hosted 35.57 million
overseas tourists during the first seven months of this year, up
12.66 percent on last year's period in spite of the financial
crisis in Asia and devastating summer floods.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists arriving from Hong Kong and Macao grew
by 15.61 percent to 30.28 million, with the total number of
foreign tourists falling by 2.63 percent to 3.97 million,
according to the China National Tourism Administration (CNTA).
</P>
<P>
China's tourism income for the period grew by 9.27 percent to
7.04 billion US dollar, according to the CNTA.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong hosted 4.17 million overseas tourists, followed by
Beijing with 1.12 million and Shanghai with 852,100 visitors.
</P>
<P>
Some 843,300 Japanese tourists visited China during the period,
with 424,900 tourists from Russia and 382,200 from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The '98 China City and Countryside Tour on offer since the
beginning of the year was designed to provide overseas tourists
with an opportunity to enjoy historical cities and rural folklore,
as well as a change to personally view the achievements of China's
reform and opening policies initiated in 1978. This year's program
follows the highly successful Visit China '97 promotion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
