<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzanian Govt Vows to Control Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Gu Ming)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government vowed to keep down the alarming rate of road accidents
which killed five people and injured 34 others daily on average
across the country.
</P>
<P>
During last three years, 5,098 people were killed and 37,624
others were injured in more than 42,000 road accidents in the
country, Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye has said.
</P>
<P>
The accidents have caused huge losses to people's lives and
property, wasting resources that could be diverted for economic
development, Sumaye deplored.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents, a pain in the flesh of the government, have
become a leading killer in the east African country together with
AIDS, malaria and cholera.
</P>
<P>
Even with relatively fewer motor vehicles, Tanzanian drivers
caused 23 times more accidents than their British counterparts --
and also beat Swedish drivers 16 times, said Chairman of the
Tanzania Roads Association (TRA), Alloyce Mushi, late last month.
</P>
<P>
About 54 percent of road accidents have been caused by
reckless driving, Sumaye said on Monday while launching a
national road safety week in Mbeya in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanians still have a fresh memory of this year's biggest
road accident in which 70 people were killed and 25 others
injured.
</P>
<P>
The reckless driver on May 3 ran the risk of bringing an
overloaded bus, christened "No Challenge," onto a flooded bridge
in the northern region of Tanga. Unfortunately, it was washed
away by turbulent into the middle of the river, causing a tragedy
that shocked and saddened the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
Drunk driving, haphazard issuance of driving licences by
corrupt policemen, poor performance of second-handed automobiles
and rough roads have also been cited by TRA as main causes of
accidents.
</P>
<P>
To bring road carnage under control, the government has
pledged to enforce traffic rules, inspect vehicles to make sure
that they are roadworthy and educate drivers as well as
vulnerable groups such as pupils, cart pullers and cyclists on
road safety.
</P>
<P>
A booklet containing "goals, responsibilities and strategies"
for enhancement of security awareness was circulated to the
public by the Dar es Salaam Road Safety Committee this week.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents have also been under fire of the local
newspapers these days, which described the road as a "death trap"
and urged the government to find effective ways in controlling
the chronic problem.
</P>
<P>
The government has raised a goal to reduce senseless road
accidents by 20 percent in six years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
