<HEADLINE>   10 Nominees for U.S. Track Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 10 candidates
including former world record holder Greg Foster and Dwight
Stones were on the ballot for the U.S. National Track and Field
Hall of Fame, it was announced in Indianapolis on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At least three of them will be inducted December 3 during the
USA Track and Field meeting in Orlando. Any candidate selected on
more than 80 percent of the ballots from Hall of Fame members,
track and field officials and athletes and selected media also
will be inducted.
</P>
<P>
Forster, 40, three time world champion in the 110-meter
hurdles,was world number one from 1977 to 1992. Stones, 44, set
three world records in the men's high jump and won bronze medals
in 1972 and 1976 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Other Olympic medalists among the candidates are Charlie
Moore, gold medalist in the 1952 Olympics in the 400-meter
hurdles; Jay Silvester, silver medalist in the men's discus at
the 1972 Olympics; and Larry Young, who won bronze medals in the
50km walk in both the 1968 and 1972 Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
