<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, U.S. Sign Accords on Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 18 (Xinhua0 -- The Bangladeshi government
Thursday signed four agreements with a United States company, AES,
for setting up a 360-MW power plant, press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The power plant with a possible cost of 200 million U.S.
dollars is to be set up at Haripur in Narayanganji district, 16
kilometers southeast of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The power plant, first land-based one in the private sector, is
to be completed in 30 months on a build-own-operation (BOO) basis,
and would start commercial operation in March 2001, according to
the agreements related to the implementation, power purchase, gas
supply and land lease issues.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government signed four agreements on setting up
four barge-mounted power plants at different points of the
country. But only one barge-mounted power plant in southwest
district of Khulna could start trial production. 
</P>
