<HEADLINE> Lhasa Launchs Protection Project for Ancient Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Ancient courtyards in Lhasa,
capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, will be preserved
and renovated during a three-year project.
</P>
<P>
An ancient courtyard called Chhungsaykung Yard, located in the
northern section of Pakhor Street in the city, has become the
first place targeted by the project. A board with Chinese
characters bearing the characters "Ancient Courtyard Under
Protection" now hangs on one side of the gate.
</P>
<P>
The city of Lhasa, with a history of more than 1,300 years, has
93 ancient courtyards with distinctive ethnic features. These
courtyards are regarded as a core of Tibetan history and culture.
</P>
<P>
The city has invested 60 million yuan in renovating and
protecting traditional Tibetan residences and ancient
buildings since the 1980s, and commission has been set up to take
charge of the work.
</P>
<P>
The commission decided to begin its protection and restoration
of ancient courtyards this year, and they expect to spend more
than ten million yuan in the effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls in 11 Districts Held in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Elections in 11 districts
in mid-western development region of Nepal began Friday morning
with no report of violence so far.
</P>
<P>
Chairman, vice chairman and members will be elected for the
district development committees (DDC) in Dolpa, Mugu, Humla,
Jumla, Kalikot, Dang, Piuthan, Banke, Bardiya, Dailekh and
Surkhet.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Election Commission said that there is no
report of violence so far and the elections are going on
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Political parties are said to form alliance with one another in
the elections, which are crucial for them in the general elections
due to be held before November 1999.
</P>
<P>
DDC elections could not be held last year in these districts
because elections for village development committees (VDC) there
were not completed due to violence by ultra-leftist guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
They were not held as well in Jajarkot, Rukum, Sallyan and
Rolpa, the other four districts in the mid-western development
region, and Gorkha, Arghakhanchi in western Nepal, Ilam in eastern
Nepal and Parsa in central Nepal, because VDC elections could not
be held there.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Election Commission said that elections
in most VDCs in the four districts in mid-western region and
Gorkha and Ilam are scheduled for September 26.
</P>
<P>
VDC polls and DDC polls have been completed this year in
Arghakhanchi and Parsa respectively.
</P>
<P>
Polls were held last year respectively for VDCs and
municipalities in May and DDCs in July in 56 of the 75 districts
in Nepal, in which the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) won a landslide victory.
</P>
<P>
But most of the mayors, deputy mayors, DDC chairmen, vice
chairmen and members elected at that time have joined the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), which broke
away from the CPN-UML in March this year and joined the government
in late August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
