<HEADLINE> Large-Screen Cinema Set for Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Lujiazui Development
Corp. based in Shanghai's Pudong New Area and US-based Bona
Co. have announced plans to build a large-screen stereo cinema in
the municipality's Pudong.
</P>
<P>
The 660-seat cinema, the firist of its kind in China, will have
a screen measuring 24 meters in height.
</P>
<P>
The jointly funded Sino-U.S. project will introduce the IMAX
film and advanced super stereophonic sound systems from Canada.
</P>
<P>
Members of the audience will be supplied with high-tech glasses
which enable them to enjoy audio and visual effects far superior
to levels characteristic of ordinary cinemas.
</P>
<P>
The facility will be located northeast of the Shanghai
television tower in the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Canadian-based IMAX built the world's first large-screen stereo
cinema in Toronto in 1971, and more than 170 IMAX cinemas
currently operating aground the world.
</P>
<P>
IMAX has a film library of over 130 special documentary films,
most of which probe the mysteries of nature and the
universe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
