<HEADLINE> Italy's Fiat Auto Company Not to Change Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The Southeast Asian financial
crisis will not lead Italian auto company Fiat to change its plans
to penetrate global markets, Fiat top executive said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the world launch of the Alfa Romeo's new luxury
saloon, the 166, Fiat Auto Managing Director Roberto Testore said
the Italian car maker's global reach had been proven by the 166's
predecessor, the 156, which was sold in 57 countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that this figure would be outstripped by the new model,
which is expected to be sold in 60 countries starting in late
October.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis would not affect Fiat's global plans. "Fiat
Auto has made a precise choice to make its industrial and
commercial efforts in countries like Brazil, Argentina, Poland,
Russia, Turkey, India and China," Testore said.
</P>
<P>
Investing in these markets means investing in the future, the
managing director said. He expected the sales to Latin America,
East Europe, India and China would rise by 50 percent by the year
2007.
</P>
<P>
Although those markets have been affected by the financial
turmoil, he stressed that Fiat would succeed in handling the
current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic market, Testore said car sales will fall from
2.4 million units last year to 1.8 million this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
