<HEADLINE> Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A total of 20 members of anti-
government armed groups laid down their arms to the government in
August, The New Light of Myanmar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
These armed group members, which include those from the ethnic
Kayin National Union (KNU), Shan State United Revolutionary Army
(SURA) and the All Burma Students' Democratic Front (ABSDF),
"exchanged arms for peace" with the government at different
military command areas.
</P>
<P>
In armed opposition to the Myanmar government, the KNU and the
ABSDF reportedly operate on the Myanmar-Thai border, while the
SURA is based in its region in eastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
In April, former KNU Central Committee member Phado Aung San
defected to the government side with more than 200 of his men in
Hpa-an, the country's Kayin state, as part of KNU's surrender.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups in
the country have made peace with the government, leaving the KNU,
led by Bo Mya, still in insurgency on the Myanmar-Thai border
although four rounds of peace talks have been held between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
The government said it still permits the turned-in armed groups
to retain their arms for "self-protection and area-defense".
</P>
</TEXT>
