<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks to Join Disarmament Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has applied for full
membership in the Conference on Disarmament so as to play a bigger
role in the disarmament process, a Foreign Ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Kitti Wasinondh, deputy Foreign Ministry spokesman, said the
application had already been forwarded to Britain's permanent
representative to the United Nations, Ian Soutar, as that country
is chairman of this year's conference, the Nation newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand, which is now an observer to the Conference on
Disarmament, applied for full membership because it recognizes the
importance of the conference. It comes at a time when the
international community, including the Southeast Asian region, is
encouraged to disarm," Kitti said.
</P>
<P>
He said Soutar has agreed to forward the Thai application to
the 60-member conference. Thailand is among 24 countries that have
applied for full membership.
</P>
<P>
Three countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) -- Indonesia, Myanmar and Vietnam -- are members of the
conference.
</P>
<P>
However, Kitti said the conference has agreed that it will put
a moratorium on new members for a while and it has not yet said
when it would resume consideration. Thailand hopes its application
will be considered when the conference decides to accept new
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
