<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Promotes Singaporean Development Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu Province, an economic
powerhouse in east China, plans to introduce the management system
used at the Suzhou Industrial Park, a Sino-Singapore joint venture
established in 1994, to other development zones in the province.
</P>
<P>
Vice Governor Wang Rongbing said the park has made outstanding
achievements in building a lean, but nonetheless efficient
administrative and civil service departments. Wang pointed out
that the park has also established a planning system based on
related laws and regulations, formed both a public welfare service
system and residential areas similar to those found in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The park has combined economic development with overall urban
planning and management in line with Singaporean practices.
</P>
<P>
The city has completed first phase construction of an eight
sq.km. section of a new industrial park which is scheduled to
enter full-scale operations early next century.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that the zone is home to 127
foreign-funded enterprises, including 109 high-tech
manufacturers. The zone has attracted foreign investments of over
4.25 billion US dollars, with the average project investments
approaching 30 million US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
