<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Said to Manipulate Sri Lanka Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's economic experts
have charged that foreign interests are manipulating Sri Lanka's
stock market, the local newspaper The Island reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Colombo's stock market suddenly took an upward surge on the
first three days of this week but slumped on Thursday. Analysts
here see this as a manifestation of profit-taking by foreign
interests who have manipulated prices.
</P>
<P>
The All Share Index (ASI) fell on Thursday by 7.19 points and
the Sensitive Index came down by 11.77. The ASI which was 506.97
on Wednesday came down to 499 Thursday while the Sensitive Index
which was 779.86 Wednesday dropped to 606.78 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the surge was due to three large parcels of prime
stocks changing hands. Also on Wednesday foreign buying amounted
to 16.36 million rupees (some 250,000 U.S. dollars) and sales went
up to 43 million rupees (650,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
But on Thursday foreign buying was limited to only 1 million
rupees while sales amounted to 15 million rupees (227,000
dollars). This meant there was an outflow of 14 million rupees
(210,000 dollars) in foreign money from the market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile economists and analysts have questioned how the
economy could be said to be surging when the Central Bank itself
has downgraded the gross domestic product growth this year from 6
to under 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The analysts also said the reason for the stagnant economy is
the artificial maintenance of the Sri Lankan rupee's value. What
they said is required is to bring down interest rates together
with a devaluation.
</P>
<P>
To make Colombo a free investment center, they added, the rupee
 should be allowed to find its level by trading in the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
