<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Voices Concern Over Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A visiting U.S. official has
voiced worries over the perspective of trade liberalization in
Asia which is reeling under an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The worsening economic situation in Asia means the United
States will not only sell less to the region, it will also find it
harder to press Asian economies to open up their markets, U.S.
Undersecretary of Commerce for International Trade David L. Aaron
said in a statement available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Aaron is leading a trade mission to Malaysia, Singapore, the
Philippines and Thailand. The mission, the first high-level U.S.
trade delegation to Asia since the crisis erupted last year, will
end its visit on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis can't be used as any kind of an excuse for backing
away from trade liberalization commitments," Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
He said the crisis has also impacted on the United States,
whose exports, after years of substantial growth, were up only 1
percent in the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. Congress will consider an additional
subscription of 14.5 billion U.S. dollars to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in support of hard-hit economies and stressed
that the IMF's funding is essential to countries such as Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"At a time when many nations throughout Asia are in need of
capital to restructure their economies, measures that make
countries less attractive to foreign investors are likely to carry
a significant cost," Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
He praised Thailand for its firm commitment to trade
liberalization and cited Malaysia's recent imposition of exchange
controls as a threat to globalization.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand does a good job in difficult times," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Thailand could be the very first nation to
recover from the crisis as it has adhered to economic reform
measures.
</P>
<P>
He said the recovery of the Southeast Asian nations will
largely depend on Japan and the growth of the region's hi-tech
industries. However, he said it is hard to predict when the
economies will rebound.
</P>
<P>
The trade delegation includes representatives from 12 U.S.
companies in telecommunications, information technology and
environment. No concrete business deals with Thai companies were
announced during the trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
