<HEADLINE> Albanian Opposition Stages New Protest, President Urges Calm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Albanian opposition staged a
new demonstration on Thursday morning pressing their demand for
the resignation of Socialist Prime Minister Fatos Nano, while
President Rexhep Mejdani urged his compatriots to show restraint.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 supporters of former president and Democratic Party
(DP) leader Sali Berisha gathered at the Skanderbeg square in
central Tirana, shouting slogans for Nano's ouster, in response to
Berisha's call for daily mass protests in defiance of a police ban.
</P>
<P>
Special army units stationed near parliament and government
offices, radio and television stations and banks have reportedly
received orders to "fire without warning on armed bandits" if they
attack state institutions.
</P>
<P>
No incidents were reported during the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Late Thursday, President Mejdani again appealed for calm in the
country, urging Albanians to show restraint so that a peaceful
solution could be found to the political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The appeal followed the approval by a parliamentary committee
of the state prosecutor's request to strip Berisha of his
parliamentary immunity on charges of masterminding armed riots.
</P>
<P>
Tirana was rocked by bloody turbulence on Monday during a
funeral procession for leading DP deputy in parliament Azem
Hajdari, who was slain by unidentified gunmen last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The motion to lift Berisha's immunity will be decided in a vote
on Friday by the full assembly, where Socialist deputies enjoy a
majority.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary committee meanwhile announced that the office
of the attorney general has the right to issue an arrest warrant
for Berisha without prior parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
Berisha reacted by ignoring the whole process, saying that he
did not "recognize the immunity at all because this parliament is
illegal."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, the Albanian government issued a statement
denouncing the DP for its role in an armed attack Wednesday night
on a police station in Lezhe some 50 kilometers north of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
During the 40-minute clash, three of the 80 assailants were
killed by police.
</P>
<P>
In related events, two high-tension wire poles near Tirana were
destroyed by bombs on Wednesday, causing the paralysis of several
private television stations.
</P>
<P>
The government warned Berisha and other DP leaders against the
use of more violence, reiterating that they would be punished if
they do not surrender their weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
