<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Textile Industries in Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Textile industries in the
Southern Common Market (Mercosur) countries are going through many
difficulties because of competitive Asian textile products, local
newspapers reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's textile production dropped 12.7 percent during the
first seven months of this year compared to the same period in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's cotton spinning output dropped 10.5 percent, and
woven-fabric production 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Its synthetic and artificial fiber production, however,
registered a slight increase.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's textile production shrank by 10 percent during the
first half of this year, while the footwear industry suffered a
54.7 percent reduction. Garment manufacturing dropped 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The leather and pelts industry, as well as knitted fabrics and
hose, registered a growth of 2.6 percent and 4.6 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the reduction is that Mercosur countries lost
their competitiveness in the face of widespread devaluation of
Asian currencies, the newspapers concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0271 </DOCNO>
