<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Industries Expanding Fast in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- High-tech industries have
emerged as new economic powerhouses in Shenzhen in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the city chalked up 39.9 billion
yuan in the output value of high-tech manufactured goods between
January and August, up 35 percent over the same period last year
and accounting for 38.8 percent of Shenzhen's total industrial
output value.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city produced 47.5 billion yuan worth of
high-tech goods, accounting for 35 percent of the city's total
industrial output value, placing it first in the country.
</P>
<P>
The city is now home to high-tech companies in industries such
as computers, telecommunications, micro-electronics, new
materials, bio-engineering, integration of machinery and
electronics, and laser, with an application rate of scientific and
technological achievements amounting to 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fast expansion of high-tech industry in this southern
Chinese city is attributed to policies and a series of
preferential measures introduced by the city to encourage the
growth of these industries.
</P>
<P>
The city has also instituted a wide range of local laws and
regulations on the protection of technologies, evaluation of
intangible assets, and technologies as a form of shares.
</P>
<P>
While increasing fiscal allocations for developing science and
technology, the city government has also been active in
constructing technological markets and setting up intermediary
organizations such as technological evaluation and arbitration
agencies. Preparations are also underway to establish a risk
fund-raising organization in the city.
</P>
<P>
The increasingly improved environment has attracted domestic
and overseas high-tech investors as well. In the first seven
months of this year, Shenzhen approved 438 overseas-financed
technology-intensive businesses, with contracts involving the use of
516 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Domestic companies such as Founder Group, a computer company
attached to Beijing University, have plans to expand into
Shenzhen. In the meantime, the city has also signed letters of
intent with 65 major universities and research institutes which
will in turn provide technical support to the development of
Shenzhen's high-tech industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
