<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palace Museum to Build New Exhibition Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 ( Xinhua ) -- Beijing's famous Palace
Museum recently announced a three-year plan to build an
underground exhibition center to house cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Curator Tan Bin said the 20,000-sq.m. center will
consist of two floors. The lower floor will feature exhibits of
gold ornaments, jewelry, diamonds and jade, with the upper floor
dedicated to paintings, calligraphy and bronzeware.
</P>
<P>
Tan said the Palace Museum, also known as Forbidden City, now
houses 930,000 cultural relics in nine categories, with 8,000
pieces exhibited each year.
</P>
<P>
He said the hall will feature the same architectural style of
the museum and will be equipped with fire prevention, air
conditioning and various other systems to protect cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The Palace Museum served as the imperial palace during both the
Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties. The complex,
which covers 720,000 sq.m., was constructed in 1420, and is the
largest and best preserved ancient building in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
