<HEADLINE> BBC ' Will Fight to Save Match of the Day' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The BBC is ready to challenge
Rupert Murdoch's proposed takeover of Manchester United, in an
attempt to save Match of the Day, according to local reports on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Corporation is concerned that BSkyB's buy-out could
threaten the future of BBC1's flagship football program.
</P>
<P>
And management are considering submitting a report to the
Office of Fair Trading listing their objections to the satellite
station's moves.
</P>
<P>
The BBC feels Sky's 623m takeover of United could prevent it
showing highlights of the club's Premiership games at Old
Trafford.
</P>
<P>
Following the announcement of the BBC's annual promises,
Corporation chairman Sir Christopher Bland said: "We would
obviously be concerned if any change in ownership in a football
club resulted in a monopoly or near monopoly.
</P>
<P>
"We would be interested to see the OFT have a long and hard
look at this issue."
</P>
<P>
But Match of the Day, which has been a fixture in the BBC
schedules for more than 30 years, broadcasts highlights of all
top-flight matches every Saturday, as part of a 73m contract with
the Premiership.
</P>
<P>
The BBC's Chief of Broadcasting Will Wyatt said: "We do not
compete with BSkyB for revenue but we compete for rights.
</P>
<P>
"We have no aspirations to take the Premier League live
contract off them but we do want to be able to renew Match of the
Day.
</P>
<P>
"Anything they got unfairly in the way of that would be
absolutely not in the interest of the public."
</P>
<P>
Mr. Wyatt added that there was a potential conflict of interes
ts in a TV company owning a football club and then selling
broadcasting rights to itself.
</P>
<P>
"Our concerns are that we will have one company sitting on
both sides of the negotiating table - and perhaps excluding
others.
</P>
<P>
"That would be absolutely anti-competitive, against public
interest and plainly wrong," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
