<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Tumen River Valley Attracts Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, September 18 (Xinhua) --The Tumen River Valley in
northeast China's Jilin Province has become an attractive location
for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, investors from 22 countries and
regions have started 735 businesses in the area, involving a total
investment of 900 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The river serves as a borderline between China and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and flows into the Sea of Japan
close to Russian territory.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, Jilin Province has made painstaking
efforts to improve the infrastructure in the valley, which falls
mainly within Korean Autonomous Prefecture of Yanbian, with
Hunchun City as the focus of development.
</P>
<P>
According to a provincial official, the Tumen River Valley is
now blessed with a newly completed 84-kilometer-long railway line
from Tumen to Changlingzi via Hunchun, 56 kilometers of which is
operational, an extended airport 115 kilometers from Hunchun, and
a number of high-grade highways connecting major cities of the
area.
</P>
<P>
Additional highways are now under construction, and railway
lines provide tours from Tumen to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The region is also connected to Russia, the DPRK and the
Republic of Korea (ROK) through three international
telecommunications lines, fiber-optic cables, and ground satellite
telecommunications station, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The city of Hunchun has installed program-controlled
switchboards capable of handling 40,000 telephone lines and a
mobile phone network capable of servicing 20,000 mobile
subscribers. With improved telecommunications facilities, Hunchun
is able to reach 180 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The city also has a power station with a designed generating
capacity of 1.2 million kilowatts. The station, with two
operational 100,000-kilowatt generating units, has started
constructing two new 300,000-kilowatt generating units.
</P>
<P>
According to a development and construction plan drafted by the
United Nations Development Program, the Tumen River Valley should
be able to attract investments of 30 billion U.S. dollars over the
next two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0283 </DOCNO>
