<HEADLINE> Mexico Sends More Police to Prevent Border Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Mexico has sent more
policemen to the border city of Juares in a bid to prevent more
killings among drug smugglers, reports here said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of two people shot in an execution-style killing
were found earlier this week in the northern city of
Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
Police believe that was a settling of accounts between drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Another alleged drug smuggler whose body was ridden with 13
shots was also discovered in Tlaquepaque, a village near the city
of Guadalajara, in the western state of Jalisco, according to
Thursday's "Mexico City Times."
</P>
<P>
Fifty-two execution-style killings have been reported this
year in the state of Jalisco.
</P>
<P>
Last week, former military and police commander Jose Arriaga
was killed when he was taking his four-year-old son to school.
</P>
<P>
Following the killing last week of Rafael Munoz Talaverta, head
of the Juarez drug cartel, more policemen were sent to the border
city of Juarez, in an effort to prevent more killings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
