<HEADLINE> Bean Can Post No Challenge to Holyfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bean takes a 32-1 record into his title bid against the heav
yweight champion, but only seven of those 33 opponents had
winning records at the time they fought him.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old failed in a bid for the IBF title when he lost
to Michael Moorer on a decision March 29, 1997. He then stopped
his next four opponents and earned a mandatory challenge to
Holyfield as the IBF's No. 1 contender. The WBN title also will
be at stake.
</P>
<P>
Holyfield, who weighed in officially at 217 pounds, retained
the WBA title and won the IBF title by stopping Moorer in the
eighth round in his last fight November 8. Bean weighed 231
pounds.
</P>
<P>
Butch Lewis has set up two title shots for Bean and the fights
are just keep him on winning. Bean said:" I just do my job and
leave the rest of it to Butch."
</P>
<P>
Lewis said that he need to keep winning to get title shots and
lucrative television matches have had a lot to do with Bean's
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Although he lost to Moorer, Bean said: "I learned a lot in the
Moorer fight for this fight. I could have thrown more punches.
It's important to be busy, to keep your hands moving."
</P>
<P>
Bean has 25 knockouts, the same as Holyfield (35-3). More than
26,000 tickets have been sold for Holyfield's first fight in his
hometown since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
