<HEADLINE> Tyson's Fate to be Decided on Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson will have to
explain to the men deciding his fate why he bit Evander
Holyfield's ears on Saturday in a hearing.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's chances of regaining his boxing license are small, and
the Nevada boxing authorities may keep him out of boxing for at
least one more year.
</P>
<P>
"The whole issue is his temper and self-control," said Nevada
Athletic Commission chairman Dr. Elias Ghanem. "Everything that
has happened since we revoked his license we have to find out
about."
</P>
<P>
Tyson is expected to get some help from a Denver
psychotherapist who has been meeting with Tyson the past week and
probably will appear to lobby on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old has begun training, and tentative plans call
for a late November or early December fight that would be
televised on pay-per-view and make Tyson earn millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
But first Tyson has to convince the same commission that had
no trouble banning him from the sport that he should be allowed
to return. He must answer question about charges two men filed
that they were attacked by Tyson following a car accident in a
Washington suburb.
</P>
<P>
The commission has only three real options: approve Tyson,
reject him or ask that he return at a later date when he can
better answer questions arising from the traffic accident.
</P>
<P>
If Tyson is rejected, he can't apply again until September 19,
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
