<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Dismisses Littlejohn Bid as "Fantasy" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- English Premier league club
Tottenham Hotspur chairman Alan Sugar dismissed as "fantasy" a
bid, headed by journalist and TV celebrity Richard Littlejohn, to
buy into the club.
</P>
<P>
Littlejohn, a lifelong Spurs fan who hosts a phone-in program
on BBC Radio Five Live, said earlier this week he had discussed
with a group of businessmen a plan to buy 29.9% of the troubled
north London club.
</P>
<P>
Sugar, who took over at White Hart Lane seven years ago, has
come under increasing pressure this season from fans who want him
to quit the club.
</P>
<P>
Sugar, a multi-millionaire who founded the Amstrad computer
company, has indicated he would consider selling his controlling
stake in Spurs for an appropriate offer.
</P>
<P>
But earlier this month he turned down an 80 million pounds
offer from leisure group ENIC.
</P>
<P>
Sugar rejected the bid by the Littlejohn consortium and said:
"Contact has been made but this is a football fan's fantasy dream
and has not been given serious attention by the board."
</P>
<P>
With BSkyB offering 623 million pounds for Manchester United
and Carlton reportedly negotiating a 275 million pounds takeover
of Arsenal, Sugar may well believe bidders are underestimating
Tottenham's worth.
</P>
<P>
Sugar has set up a new independent phone-in line at Tottenham
to"tell fans the truth" about press stories.
</P>
<P>
He has handed control of the Media Monitor service to new
director Martin Peters, a former Tottenham and England star.
</P>
<P>
Spurs have won only once this season, have twice lost 3-0 at
home this year and if they lose against bottom-of-the-table
Southampton on Saturday, Sugar could find the crisis spiralling
out of control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
