<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Ministers Under Soeharto's Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- All ministers under
Indonesian former president Soeharto's New Order government must
disclose details of their personal wealth, Justice Minister Muladi
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The mistakes of the New Order cannot be blamed just on
Soeharto. All ministers and high-ranking officials under Soeharto
must also be investigated, including President B.J. Habibie,"
Muladi was quoted by the Indonesian Observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto stepped down on May 21 during the country's worst
political and economic crisis in decades. He was replaced by his
running mate Habibie, one of the longest serving ministers of the
Soeharto regime.
</P>
<P>
After taking office, President Habibie pledged sweeping
economic and political reforms in a bid to create a clean
government, free from the corrupt, collusive and nepotistic
practices that flourished during Soeharto's 32-year reign.
</P>
<P>
"President Habibie must also fill in the form," Muladi said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the investigation into the wealth of
ministers would not be conducted in haste. The first priority was
to investigate the wealth of the former president.
</P>
<P>
Local as well as foreign media have accused Soeharto, his
children and other relatives of illegally amassing wealth during
his 32-year rule.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto is also accused of issuing decrees and instructions
that benefited his children and close friends.
</P>
<P>
The government announced Wednesday it had set up a three-member
team to probe Soeharto. Led by Attorney General Andi M. Ghalib,
the team comprises the chief of the Indonesian Police and head of
the state auditing body.
</P>
<P>
Muladi Thursday also announced the establishment of a new team
focusing on probing Soeharto's overseas wealth. The team would be
headed by Coordinating Minister for Development Supervision and
Administrative Reform Hartarto Satrosoenarto and Attorney General
Ghalib.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident of the government's political will to probe
Soeharto's wealth and that they will do their best. Otherwise, it
will mean the government is lying to the people. Our side is
confident there is the possibility Soeharto may be jailed if proof
of criminal acts and abuse of power is found," Muladi said.
</P>
<P>
On a separate occasion, State Secretary/Minister Akbar Tandjung
said Hartarto and Ghalib will soon meet Soeharto at the latter's
residence to seek confirmation and clarification about his recent
statement that he did not have "a single cent" in any bank account
abroad.
</P>
<P>
In a statement broadcast by his daughter's television station
early this month, Soeharto said he did not have a single cent in
savings abroad. He also challenged anyone to prove allegations
that he had a personal fortune both overseas and at home.
</P>
<P>
American magazine Forbes estimated in July that Soeharto
amassed a fortune worth 4 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Chelsea Wins Opening Match at Cup Winners's Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Chelsea
had a hard work to beat Swedes Helsingborg 1-0 in the opening
match of the European Cup Winners' Cup on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The London club were not alone in struggling against
lowly-ranked opponents.
</P>
<P>
Italian big-spenders Lazio, German representatives MSV
Duisburg and Paris St Germain were all held 1-1 at home by teams
who rarely feature in the later rounds.
</P>
<P>
Mallorca of Spain bucked the trend with a well-earned 1-0 win
in Scotland against Hearts while Heerenveen flew the Dutch flag
with a 3-1 win over Amica Wronki of Poland.
</P>
<P>
No team has ever retained the Cup Winners' Cup but, in what
could be its last year of existence, Chelsea would have fancied
their chances looking at this season's threadbare field.
</P>
<P>
But they had only Franck Lebouef's 43rd minute free kick to
show for their efforts against a team who knocked Aston Villa out
of the UEFA Cup two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Italian international Pierluigi Casiraghi hit a post with his
first touch after coming on as a second-half substitute but
Chelsea deserved little more.
</P>
<P>
Lazio, runners-up in last season's UEFA Cup, spent close on
100 million U.S. dollars in the close season but made a
disastrous start against Lausanne Sports when young midfielder
Dejan Stankovic was sent off after just two minutes for handling
a goal-bound shot.
</P>
<P>
Fabio Celestini's resultant penalty was saved by Luca
Marchegiani and Lazio then went ahead when Pavel Nedved headed
home a Marcelo Salas cross in the 37th minute.
</P>
<P>
But the Swiss grew in confidence after the break and in the
54th minute, Philippe Douglas side-footed in a cross from Marc
Hottiger for a deserved draw.
</P>
<P>
Duisburg, back in Europe after a 19-year absence, needed an
83rd minute goal by substitute Marcus Wedau to salvage a draw
against 10-man Genk.
</P>
<P>
The Belgians had midfielder Marc Hendrikx sent off in the 57th
minute but went ahead four minutes later with a header by Finland
midfielder Juha Reini from a corner.
</P>
<P>
PSG, winners in 1996, were lackluster throughout as they were
held by Israel's Maccabi Haifa.
</P>
<P>
The Parisians, who were also losing finalists in 1997, opened
the scoring with a Marco Simone penalty in the 82nd minute but
the Israelis hit back five minutes later thanks to gifted striker
Yosi Benayoun.
</P>
<P>
Mallorca made a flying start to their first season in Europe,
beating Hearts with a messy goal in the 17th minute when home
'keeper Gilles Rousset punched a corner straight on to the chest
of Elena Marcelino and saw the ball bounce into the net.
</P>
<P>
Heerenveen beat Amica Wronki 3-1 with goals from Jeffrey
Talan, Dumitru Mitrita and Boudewijn Pahlplatz. Grzegorz Krol's
reply kept the Poles in the tie.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle, like Chelsea, face an awkward second leg after
scraping a 2-1 home win over Partizan Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Alan Shearer put Ruud Gullit's side ahead after 12 minutes but
a Vuk Rasovic penalty levelled in the 68th. Greek defender
Nikolaos Dabizas headed the winner three minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Austrian side Ried marked their European debut with a 2-0 home
victory over MTK Budapest. Gerald Strafner and Ronald Brunmayr
stunned the 20-time Hungarian champions.
</P>
<P>
Goals by Yevgeny Kharlachev and Zaza Dzhanashia gave Lokomotiv
Moscow a comfortable 2-0 win at Ukrainian side CSKA Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Lokomotiv, semifinalists last season, controlled the match and
had too much experience and pace up front.
</P>
<P>
Besiktas of Turkey beat Spartak Trnava of Slovakia 3-0, FC
Copenhagen collected a useful 2-0 away win against Levski Sofia
and Panionios Athens beat Finnish side Haka Valkeakoski 2-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
