<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Americans Favor Full Payment of U.N. Dues, Poll Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Most Americans asked
in a recent poll disagreed with the U.S. lawmakers' failure to pay
U.S. back dues, and said that the United Nations is doing a very
good job, so they wanted Washington to pay an estimated 1.6
billion U.S. dollars in arrears.
</P>
<P>
By a three-to-one margin, those Americans polled favored
Congress paying the money the United States owes. And 49 percent
of those advocating payment are so concerned about the issue that
it would affect their vote for lawmakers, said the poll sponsored
by the United Nations Association (UNA) of the USA.
</P>
<P>
"The public supports the United Nations more eagerly and with
more enthusiasm than Congress does," John Whitehead, chairman of
the UNA, said. "There's some kind of disconnect between public
opinion about the United Nations and the voting record of
Congress, at least in recent years."
</P>
<P>
Support for the United Nations among Americans has risen an
average of 10 percentage points since the previous poll which was
conducted two years ago, Whitehead, a former deputy secretary of
state, said.
</P>
<P>
The UNA was founded about the same time as the United Nations
was founded some 50 years ago. A national organization to educate
the people about the importance of the United Nations, it
advocates that the Clinton administration should pay back dues in
full, on time and without condition.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the group Wirthin Worldwide, came at
a time when the United States is a main contributor to the current
financial crisis in the United Nations and threatened with a loss
of its vote in the General Assembly if it fails to pay a chunk of
the money it owes.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that 60 percent of respondents said that the
United Nations is doing "a very good job," the organization's
highest approval rating since 1959 and up from 49 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-two percent said that they saw the world body as "very
important" for American policy engagement, up from 54 percent in
the 1996 survey. In sharp contrast, the ratings for other
international organizations such as NATO and the World Bank remain
unchanged, the poll said.
</P>
<P>
Eight percent of Americans surveyed voiced their rejection of
condition being attached to the due payment, and 43 percent of
those asked approved the job performance of United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, it said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congressional leaders have in the past linked
legislation that would pay off U.N. arrears with conditions that
the world body conduct reform under America-favoring programs. The
U.S. failure to pay back its dues in full, on time and without
condition has been met with strong criticism from among a majority
of U.N. member states.
</P>
<P>
At the current session of the General Assembly, the financial
crisis in the U.N. and Washington's unwillingness to pay its
outstanding contributions are expected to be high on the agenda
during the general debate, which will kick off on September 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
