<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mechanism Proposed to Monitor Financial Flows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- An international
mechanism has been proposed to monitor financial and monetary
flows to fence off negative effects of globalization, Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks on behalf of the group of 77 developing
countries and China at the U.N. high-level meeting on
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Since there is the World Trade Organization for matters of
international trade, a financial monitoring mechanism is
reasonably needed to help mitigate the unpredictability and dire
effects of globalization, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the United Nations should remain a vital and
effective instrument of international cooperation for
"people-centered and people-driven" development.
</P>
<P>
Didier Opertti, president of the U.N. General Assembly, told
the meeting that within the present framework, the U.N. dialogue
on globalization reflects the need to coordinate new international
mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that international financial institutions have
not been able to prevent the current crises and other mechanisms
including those at the United Nations have not been successful,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Austria's Georg Lennkh, speaking on behalf of the European
Union, said market forces alone would not resolve the problems of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Universal acceptance of certain societal values are required
and the United Nations provides a unique platform for such "global
housekeeping", he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980918.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Cooperation Important: Qin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 17 (Xinhua) -- Economic globalization
is inter-dependence in the real sense of the term, said Chinese
Permanent Representative to the U.N. Ambassador Qin Huasun here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the high-level meeting of the U.N. General
Assembly, Qin said that in the tide of globalization, the
sustainable development of the world economy cannot be achieved
without deeper and wider international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The execution of responsible economic and financial policies by
the major developed countries holds the key to the stability and
growth of the world economy, he said, adding that this should
become an important component of international cooperation in this
new era.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the developing countries are striving to join the
process of economic globalization from a position of disadvantage
and under unequal conditions. With a weak capacity to withstand
the hazards in the financial and other fields, they need
meaningful international support, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, inequality still exists in international
economy relations, the new "rules of the game" in the
international economic, trade, environmental and other fields have
not reflected the interests of developing countries in an
equitable manner.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the developing and developed nations has not
shown signs of narrowing, and some developing countries are in
real danger of being marginalized in the globalization process, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In formulating new "rules of the game," efforts should be made
to guarantee the effective participation of the developing
nations, and sufficient consideration should be given to their
specific problems, Ambassador Qin noted.
</P>
<P>
The financial, technical and other kinds of assistance to
developing countries should be strengthened to boost their
capacity building, he added.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Asian economic crisis, Qin said the most
important task before the United Nations now is to help those
countries hard hit by the crisis to resume healthy economic and
social development.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the Asian financial crisis is global and it will
require concerted efforts by the world community to fully
eliminate its consequences, the Chinese representative said.
</P>
<P>
Major developed nations with significant influence on the
economy of the Asian region should take constructive policy
measures as early as possible by contributing to the stabilization
of the situation and rejuvenation of the economy in the region,
Qin said in conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
